  </p>
<div class="policy-family" id="fam-leg-sys">
<div class="family-header">
<span class="family-code">LEG</span>
<span class="family-title">SYS: System Principles</span>
<span class="family-count">2/2 active</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-grid">
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-SYSR-0001">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-SYSR-0001</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Legislature must reflect democracy with power safeguards</p><p class="rule-plain">Congress must represent the people fairly while protecting against any one group gaining too much power or trampling on the rights of others.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Legislative power must reflect democratic representation while maintaining safeguards against concentration of power, instability, and majoritarian abuse.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Democratic representation is the foundational principle, but systems must also guard against concentration, instability, and majoritarian abuse. These twin requirements define the design space for legislative reform.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-SYSR-0002">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-SYSR-0002</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">No persistent minority governance without democratic justification</p><p class="rule-plain">A smaller group of people cannot be given permanent control over government just because of where they live or how districts are drawn.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Legislative structures may not grant disproportionate and persistent governing power to minority populations without sufficient democratic justification.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Structural minority rule, where a minority population consistently controls or blocks national policy, lacks democratic legitimacy. This rule requires that any such arrangement be specifically and currently justified rather than historically inherited.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="policy-family" id="fam-leg-str">
<div class="family-header">
<span class="family-code">LEG</span>
<span class="family-title">STR: Structural Reform</span>
<span class="family-count">1/1 active</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-grid">
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-STRS-0001">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-STRS-0001</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Bicameralism retained but each chamber needs distinct purpose</p><p class="rule-plain">If Congress keeps both the House and Senate, each chamber must serve a clear and different democratic purpose, not just duplicate each other.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">The legislature may retain a bicameral structure, but each chamber must have a clearly distinct democratic function and justification.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Maintaining two chambers is not inherently undemocratic, but each chamber must serve a clearly justified democratic function. Historical inertia is not sufficient justification for structural imbalance between chambers.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="policy-family" id="fam-leg-hse">
<div class="family-header">
<span class="family-code">LEG</span>
<span class="family-title">HSE: House Reform</span>
<span class="family-count">3/3 active</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-grid">
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-HSES-0001">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-HSES-0001</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">House must represent population proportionally as primary body</p><p class="rule-plain">The House of Representatives must be the main lawmaking body, with seats divided based on population so every American gets equal representation.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">The House of Representatives must be the primary democratic legislative body, with representation proportional to population.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">The House is designed to be the primary democratic legislative chamber with proportional representation. Affirming this principle establishes the baseline against which House reform should be measured.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-HSES-0002">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-HSES-0002</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">House must expand to restore representational accuracy</p><p class="rule-plain">The House must grow to include more representatives so each district is smaller and members of Congress can better know and serve their communities.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">House representation must be expanded or restructured to reduce district size and improve representational accuracy.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">With 761,000 constituents per representative on average, the current House size makes meaningful representation structurally impossible. Expansion is necessary to restore the House to its democratic purpose.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-HSES-0003">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-HSES-0003</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">House is primary origin of fiscal and domestic legislation</p><p class="rule-plain">The House of Representatives should be the primary chamber where bills about spending, taxes, and domestic policies are introduced and debated first.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">The House must be the primary origin of fiscal legislation, domestic policy, and general lawmaking authority.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Affirming the House's primary role in fiscal legislation and general lawmaking authority establishes the constitutional logic for House expansion and filibuster reform. This clarifies the democratic hierarchy between the two chambers.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-HSES-0004">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-HSES-0004</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Expand the House of Representatives to at least 600 members under the Wyoming Rule; repeal the 1929 apportionment cap; cap congressional districts at 575,000 constituents</p><p class="rule-plain">The House must expand to at least 600 members under the Wyoming Rule, which ensures the smallest state gets one representative and all others get proportional seats based on their population.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">The House of Representatives must be expanded to at least 600 members as an immediate statutory floor, with the Permanent Apportionment Act of 1929 repealed and the Wyoming Rule enacted as the governing sizing principle for all future apportionments. A statutory trigger must require automatic House expansion whenever any congressional district exceeds 575,000 constituents following a decennial census. A constitutional amendment must establish the Wyoming Rule as a minimum apportionment standard, preventing any future Congress from re-imposing an arbitrary seat cap. House expansion must not dilute minority voting strength and must be accompanied by proportional Voting Rights Act compliance review.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Legal basis: Permanent Apportionment Act of 1929, Pub. L. No. 71-13, 46 Stat. 26 (capping the House at 435 seats -- this statute must be repealed; it is a statute, not a constitutional provision, and may be changed by simple majority legislation); U.S. Const. art. I, § 2, cl. 3 (requires apportionment among states according to population -- does not require 435 seats or any particular district size); Wesberry v. Sanders, 376 U.S. 1 (1964) (requiring congressional districts to be as equal in population as practicable -- expansion would reduce the difficulty of achieving population equality across all districts); Voting Rights Act of 1965, 52 U.S.C. § 10301 et seq. (any expansion plan must comply with VRA Section 2 requirements not to dilute minority voting strength). Empirical evidence: The House was capped at 435 members when the U.S. population was approximately 106 million; the 2020 Census recorded 331 million people; the average House district now contains approximately 761,000 constituents, larger than the entire population of several states at the time of the Founding; the Wyoming Rule would yield approximately 573 seats and the Cube Root Rule would yield approximately 693 seats under 2020 census data; most OECD democracies have significantly higher representative-to-constituent ratios than the U.S. House; the 435-seat cap means Wyoming's single at-large representative and California's 52 representatives average approximately 750,000 people per district, producing inconsistent representation across states. Enforcement mechanisms: Statutory expansion mandate with automatic trigger -- removes the need for a future Congress to affirmatively vote for expansion; VRA compliance review requirement -- ensures expansion cannot be used to dilute minority voting strength; constitutional amendment pursuit -- prevents re-imposition of an arbitrary cap without supermajority approval. PolicyOS compliance: KERN-0004 (reducing the constituent-to-representative ratio is a democratic accountability mechanism -- representatives with smaller constituencies are more accessible and accountable); DEMO-0001 (making representation more proportional to population directly advances democratic representation). Adversarial review: Gap -- this rule addresses seat count but not district boundaries; expanding seats without independent redistricting reform will simply create more gerrymandered districts at a smaller scale; VRA compliance review is necessary but not sufficient to prevent partisan manipulation of the newly created districts. Loophole -- Congress could "expand" the House while drawing new districts to pack opposition voters, creating the appearance of expansion while entrenching partisan advantage; the statute must require that new seat assignments be drawn by independent redistricting commissions subject to the same standards as existing seats. Unintended consequence -- expanding the House to 600+ members significantly increases the cost and logistical complexity of congressional operations; appropriations for expanded operations must be mandatory, not left to annual votes by the now-larger membership. Abuse path -- a president and majority party could time expansion to take effect after a census that advantaged their geography; the automatic trigger mechanism must operate independently of partisan timing, with expansion required following each decennial census whenever the threshold is exceeded regardless of which party is in power.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="policy-family" id="fam-leg-sen">
<div class="family-header">
<span class="family-code">LEG</span>
<span class="family-title">SEN: Senate Reform</span>
<span class="family-count">4/4 active</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-grid">
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-SENS-0001">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-SENS-0001</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Senate may use population-weighted voting to reduce imbalance</p><p class="rule-plain">The Senate could give more voting power to senators from larger states so small-state residents don't have vastly more influence than big-state residents.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">The Senate may be restructured to preserve state representation while incorporating population-weighted voting to reduce extreme representational imbalance.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Population-weighted voting within the Senate would preserve state representation while reducing the extreme democratic imbalance between states like Wyoming and California. This is among the less structurally disruptive reform paths.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-SENS-0002">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-SENS-0002</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Senate may include both state-based and population-based seats</p><p class="rule-plain">The Senate could be restructured to include some seats based on state equality and some based on population, balancing small-state representation with fairness to all voters.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">The Senate may include both state-based representatives and population-based representatives to balance federal and democratic principles.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">A hybrid model combining state-based representatives with population-based representatives could balance federal structure against democratic representation. This mirrors approaches used in upper chambers in some parliamentary systems.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-SENS-0003">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-SENS-0003</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Senate may serve as review body rather than co-equal veto chamber</p><p class="rule-plain">Instead of being an equal lawmaking partner, the Senate could become a review chamber that can delay or suggest changes to House bills but not permanently block them.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">The Senate may serve as a review, delay, and revision body rather than a co-equal veto chamber for all legislation.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Redesigning the Senate as a review, delay, and revision body rather than a co-equal veto chamber would preserve deliberation while eliminating permanent minority blockade. This aligns the Senate with the role of upper chambers in most peer democracies.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-SENS-0004">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-SENS-0004</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">House may have final legislative authority after Senate review</p><p class="rule-plain">The House could have the final say on legislation after the Senate has reviewed it, ensuring the chamber that best represents the American people makes the ultimate decision.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Final legislative authority may rest with the House in defined circumstances after Senate review or delay.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Giving the House final legislative authority after a Senate review period would allow the democratically representative chamber to ultimately decide national policy. This resolves the fundamental tension between state and popular sovereignty.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-SENS-0005">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-SENS-0005</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Enact DC statehood and Puerto Rico statehood immediately; pursue structural Senate reform to reduce extreme population-to-representation imbalances through statehood, territorial representation, and constitutional amendment</p><p class="rule-plain">Washington, D.C. and Puerto Rico must be admitted as states immediately, and structural reforms to the Senate must be pursued to reduce the unfair advantage small states have over large ones.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Congress must immediately enact DC and Puerto Rico statehood as standalone legislation without preconditions, paired with full House and Senate representation for each new state. Full voting representation in Congress must be extended to all populated U.S. territories -- Guam, the U.S. Virgin Islands, American Samoa, and the Northern Mariana Islands -- pending statehood. A constitutional amendment commission must be tasked with developing proposals for population-weighted Senate voting, hybrid representation structures, or other mechanisms to reduce the per-capita representation disparity. A statutory annual Senate equity index, published by the Congressional Research Service, must document per-capita Senate representation ratios by state and territory to maintain democratic accountability for the structural deficit. Any resident of DC or a U.S. territory must have a private right of action to challenge any federal statute or regulation that discriminates against non-state jurisdictions in the allocation of federal benefits, obligations, or programs available to residents of the 50 states.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Legal basis: U.S. Const. art. IV, § 3 (granting Congress full authority to admit new states -- DC and Puerto Rico statehood can be enacted by simple majority legislation); District of Columbia Admission Act, H.R. 51, 117th Cong. (2021) (passed the House but was blocked by Senate filibuster -- the statutory framework is developed and ready); Puerto Rico Status Act (multiple versions considered in 117th-119th Congresses); U.S. Const. art. V (rendering the equal-state-suffrage rule in the Senate formally unamendable without unanimous state consent -- this is the constitutional constraint that makes statehood the near-term reform path and constitutional amendment the long-term path); Dahl, R. A. (2002). How democratic is the American Constitution? Yale University Press (documenting the anti-majoritarian character of the Senate with no parallel in advanced democracies). Empirical evidence: Wyoming's approximately 581,000 residents hold the same two Senate votes as California's 39 million, a per-capita representation ratio of approximately 67:1; Washington, DC has a population of approximately 700,000 -- larger than Wyoming or Vermont -- pays full federal taxes and has contributed military personnel to every American war, yet has zero voting representation in Congress; Puerto Rico has a population of approximately 3.2 million -- larger than 21 states -- and all residents are U.S. citizens by birth, yet have zero voting representation in Congress; the Senate's anti-majoritarian structure means the 26 smallest states, representing approximately 18% of the U.S. population, can elect a majority of the Senate; the filibuster has blocked DC and Puerto Rico statehood bills that passed the House with clear majority support. Enforcement mechanisms: Simple majority statehood legislation -- removes the supermajority threshold that has previously blocked progress; private right of action for territory residents -- creates a judicial enforcement path for discrimination against non-state jurisdictions; CRS equity index -- creates a public accountability mechanism and political pressure for structural reform; constitutional amendment commission -- provides institutional structure for developing long-term reform proposals. PolicyOS compliance: KERN-0004 (granting DC and Puerto Rico statehood directly creates new democratic accountability mechanisms -- two new senators and additional House representatives who are accountable to currently disenfranchised populations); DEMO-0001 (extending voting representation to currently disenfranchised U.S. citizens is a direct application of democratic representation principles). Adversarial review: Gap -- DC and Puerto Rico statehood may pass the Senate only with elimination or carve-out of the filibuster for statehood legislation; this rule should be read in conjunction with filibuster reform (LEGL-PROS-0005 and LEGL-FILB-0001/0002) which must be pursued in parallel or the statehood pathway is blocked procedurally even with majority support. Loophole -- a state government could argue that adding new states without unanimous consent effectively modifies the equal-state-suffrage rule in the Senate (Article V), even though Article IV grants Congress clear admission authority; the constitutional amendment commission's work should specifically address this argument and develop a legal record supporting the straightforward Article IV interpretation. Unintended consequence -- DC statehood raises questions about the constitutional requirement of a "District" not exceeding 10 square miles for the seat of government (U.S. Const. art. I, § 8, cl. 17); the statehood legislation must retain a small federal enclave around the Capitol and core federal buildings to satisfy this constitutional requirement. Abuse path -- a Senate majority could condition DC or Puerto Rico statehood on concessions unrelated to the statehood itself (policy riders, constitutional provisions in the state constitution) that effectively diminish the value of the new state's representation; the statute must prohibit conditions on statehood beyond those required for constitutional compliance.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="policy-family" id="fam-leg-pro">
<div class="family-header">
<span class="family-code">LEG</span>
<span class="family-title">PRO: Procedure Reform</span>
<span class="family-count">2/2 active</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-grid">
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-PROS-0001">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-PROS-0001</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Filibuster and indefinite minority obstruction must end</p><p class="rule-plain">The Senate filibuster, which allows a small minority to block legislation indefinitely, must be abolished because it's undemocratic and prevents majority rule.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Legislative procedure may not allow indefinite minority obstruction of legislation through mechanisms such as unlimited debate without resolution.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Unlimited debate without resolution is not a constitutional requirement but a Senate procedural rule that has been transformed into a permanent minority veto. Eliminating or strictly limiting it restores the basic function of a deliberative body.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-PROS-0002">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-PROS-0002</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Systems must resolve persistent deadlock between chambers</p><p class="rule-plain">When the House and Senate can't agree on legislation, there must be a fair process to resolve the deadlock rather than letting bills die forever.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Legislative systems must include mechanisms to resolve persistent deadlock between chambers without indefinite paralysis.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Legislative systems that can deadlock indefinitely without resolution mechanisms fail at their basic function of producing law. Built-in resolution mechanisms are a prerequisite for functional governance.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-PROS-0003">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-PROS-0003</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Discharge petition reform, lower threshold and automatic scheduling for bills with supermajority support</p><p class="rule-plain">If a majority of House members sign a petition to vote on a bill, it must automatically be scheduled for a floor vote within a short time, preventing leaders from blocking popular legislation.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Any bill that obtains signatures from a majority of House members (218 of 435) on a discharge petition must be automatically scheduled for a floor vote within 10 legislative days, without the ability of the Speaker or Rules Committee to block or delay the vote. The current 218-signature threshold is retained, but the procedural barriers that have historically rendered discharge petitions ineffective, including the 30-legislative-day delay, closed petition rolls, and leadership scheduling control, must be eliminated. Any member may view the current signature count in real time through the House Clerk's public database.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">The discharge petition is the constitutional mechanism for the majority to force a floor vote over the Speaker's objection, yet it has rarely succeeded in the modern House because leadership controls scheduling and can impose procedural costs on members who sign. Since 1935, fewer than 25 discharge petitions have succeeded in reaching a House floor vote. Discharge reform does not override the Speaker; it provides a backstop ensuring that a genuine floor majority cannot be indefinitely blocked by leadership gatekeeping. [Adversarial review per PAOS-TEST-0008] The 218-signature threshold means the mechanism is available only to genuine cross-party or intra-majority coalitions, minority parties cannot trigger it alone, limiting its use to situations where leadership is blocking its own caucus rather than simply blocking the minority. Immediate public disclosure of signatures creates a chilling effect: leadership can identify and apply political or financial pressure to members during the assembly process before the threshold is reached, potentially deterring participation. The requirement that the Speaker "cannot block or delay" the vote lacks an explicit enforcement mechanism; a non-compliant Speaker creates a constitutional confrontation with no clear resolution path short of a floor override vote. The 10-legislative-day window does not specify the debate or amendment process governing floor consideration, leaving open the risk that a bill reaches the floor under a closed rule controlled by the same leadership the petition was designed to circumvent.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-PROS-0004">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-PROS-0004</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Proxy voting prohibited for floor votes; remote voting infrastructure mandated for public health and emergency continuity</p><p class="rule-plain">Members of Congress cannot vote on behalf of absent colleagues on final floor votes, but secure remote voting technology must be available for emergencies like pandemics.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Members of Congress must be physically or remotely present and cast their own votes on all floor votes; proxy voting, allowing one member to cast another member's vote in their absence, is prohibited on final passage votes. Congress must invest in verified, secure remote voting infrastructure that enables members to vote from their home districts during declared national public health emergencies, natural disasters, or other circumstances that make physical travel to Washington genuinely dangerous. Remote voting must require biometric or multi-factor authentication and produce a verifiable vote record.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Congress authorized proxy voting during the COVID-19 pandemic (2020–2022) as a temporary measure, generating constitutional controversy and accountability concerns. Proxy voting for routine business undermines the democratic premise that members personally cast the votes they are accountable for. However, the pandemic revealed the urgent need for remote voting infrastructure as a continuity mechanism. The solution is to prohibit proxy voting while mandating the remote participation technology that makes physical absence unnecessary for representing one's constituents. [Adversarial review per PAOS-TEST-0008] The rule does not define who declares that physical travel is "genuinely dangerous", if the majority party controls this determination, it could be applied selectively to enable remote voting for allies while requiring in-person attendance from the opposing party during contested votes. Biometric authentication systems have documented failure modes for members with disabilities, darker skin tones, or other characteristics that reduce recognition accuracy; the "multi-factor" alternative requires an explicit fallback process to avoid disenfranchising affected members. Prohibiting proxy voting entirely without a medical-emergency carve-out short of a full declared national disaster could force members to choose between their constituents' representation and receiving medical treatment for serious but non-emergency conditions. The remote voting infrastructure mandate lacks a specific funding floor or implementation deadline, meaning the prohibition on proxy voting could take legal effect before secure remote infrastructure exists.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-PROS-0005">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-PROS-0005</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Eliminate the Senate filibuster for all legislation by majority rule change; restore the talking filibuster as an immediate interim step; carve out voting rights and democracy legislation without delay</p><p class="rule-plain">The Senate filibuster must be eliminated for all legislation through a majority-rule change to Senate procedures, allowing bills to pass with 51 votes instead of requiring 60.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">The Senate must eliminate the legislative filibuster by majority rule change at the earliest available opportunity. As an immediate interim step, the Senate must restore the talking filibuster, requiring senators opposing legislation to hold the Senate floor continuously -- standing and speaking without adjournments, proxies, or substitutes -- for the full duration of any delay. An immediate, unconditional filibuster carve-out must be enacted for all voting rights and democracy legislation, effective in the current Congress. Additional carve-outs must be adopted for constitutional amendment resolutions, statehood legislation, and Supreme Court structural reform legislation. A standing Senate rule must require that any future restoration of the filibuster be approved by a 2/3 supermajority of the full Senate, not merely those present and voting.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Legal basis: U.S. Const. art. I, § 5 (each chamber may determine its own rules of proceedings by majority vote -- the filibuster is not mentioned in the Constitution and may be eliminated by a simple majority vote at the start of any Congress); Senate Rule XXII (the current cloture rule requiring 60 votes -- this is a Senate rule, not a constitutional provision, and can be changed by majority vote using the "nuclear option" or at the beginning of a new Congress); precedents of 2013 and 2017 (Senate eliminated the filibuster for executive and judicial nominations using exactly the majority-rule procedure available for legislative business); Koger, G. (2010). Filibustering: A political history of obstruction in the House and Senate. University of Chicago Press. Empirical evidence: The current filibuster requires 60 votes to invoke cloture and end debate on legislation, enabling 41 senators representing as few as 11% of the U.S. population to permanently block majority will without holding the floor, speaking a word, or engaging with the substance of legislation; in its current form the filibuster has been used to block the John R. Lewis Voting Rights Advancement Act, the Freedom to Vote Act, the Equality Act, gun safety legislation, immigration reform, and climate legislation, all of which passed the House with majority support; the filibuster as practiced requires no floor presence, no speech, and no engagement -- a senator may block legislation by filing a single procedural notice; the Senate has already abolished the filibuster for executive and lower-court nominations (2013) and Supreme Court nominations (2017). Enforcement mechanisms: Majority rule change at start of Congress -- requires no Senate supermajority to implement; talking filibuster requirement -- creates a political cost for blocking legislation without engagement on the merits; carve-outs for voting rights and structural reform categories -- prevents the filibuster from blocking the specific categories of legislation most essential to democratic reform; 2/3 supermajority requirement to restore the filibuster -- prevents a future Senate majority from easily reimposing obstruction. PolicyOS compliance: KERN-0004 (filibuster elimination directly enables democratic majority governance -- allowing 41 senators representing 11% of the population to permanently veto majority will is incompatible with democratic accountability); DEMO-0001 (the talking filibuster requires senators to engage publicly with the merits of legislation they oppose, creating accountability to their constituents for obstruction). Adversarial review: Gap -- eliminating the filibuster gives simple majorities unrestricted power to pass legislation, including legislation that violates minority rights; this creates a need for robust constitutional protections (see other pillars on rights and courts) to check majoritarian excess; the filibuster's elimination must be understood as a package with other structural reforms. Loophole -- a Senate majority could carve out the "voting rights" exception so narrowly that most voting rights legislation doesn't qualify, while pointing to the exception as evidence of good faith; the carve-out must be defined to include any legislation affecting ballot access, voter registration, election administration, redistricting, campaign finance, or congressional representation. Unintended consequence -- eliminating the filibuster means a simple Senate majority can pass legislation that a future majority immediately repeals, creating policy volatility; the talking filibuster as an interim step allows genuine deliberation while reducing strategic obstruction and may achieve more durable reform. Abuse path -- a majority could use simple majority rule to pass structural reforms that entrench their own power before an election (statehood bills designed to favor their party, partisan redistricting measures, electoral college changes) at which point the loss of the filibuster becomes a tool of anti-democratic consolidation rather than democratic reform; the carve-out structure must be accompanied by anti-entrenchment principles limiting the use of majority rule for changes that directly benefit the majority enacting them.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-PROS-0006">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-PROS-0006</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Automatic continuing resolution rule, all agencies remain funded at prior-year levels if Congress fails to enact appropriations by the deadline; government shutdowns must be eliminated as a governing tool</p><p class="rule-plain">If Congress hasn't passed a budget by the deadline, all government agencies automatically continue to be funded at their previous year's level, preventing shutdowns from being used as political weapons.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">A statutory automatic continuing resolution mechanism must be enacted providing: (1) if Congress fails to enact new appropriations legislation or a conventional continuing resolution for any federal agency or program by the applicable fiscal year deadline, that agency or program is automatically funded at 100% of its prior-year enacted appropriations level on a pro-rated daily basis; (2) automatic continuing resolutions remain in effect until superseded by enacted appropriations legislation, with no expiration date and no additional legislative action required; (3) automatic CR funding levels are adjusted annually for inflation at the applicable CPI rate to prevent gradual real-dollar defunding through inaction; (4) the Office of Management and Budget must publish a publicly accessible, real-time dashboard showing every agency's appropriations status and the duration of any automatic CR; and (5) any federal employee or contractor who suffers demonstrable economic harm due to a shutdown caused by deliberate congressional inaction must have a private right of action for back pay, damages, and injunctive relief in federal court.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Legal basis: 31 U.S.C. § 1341 (Antideficiency Act -- prohibiting agencies from spending beyond their appropriations, which makes the absence of an automatic CR create immediate operational paralysis); Consolidated Appropriations Act, various years (the annual appropriations process that automatic CRs would supplement); U.S. Const. art. I, § 9, cl. 7 (Appropriations Clause -- money may be drawn from the Treasury only in consequence of appropriations made by law; the automatic CR statute satisfies this requirement by being the law authorizing continued spending); Congressional Budget and Impoundment Control Act of 1974, Pub. L. No. 93-344 (establishing the modern appropriations process -- an automatic CR supplement can operate within this framework without requiring constitutional amendment). Empirical evidence: The 2018-2019 partial government shutdown lasted 35 days and cost an estimated $11 billion according to the Congressional Budget Office, including $3 billion in permanent economic losses that were never recovered; federal employees were furloughed or required to work without pay; critical agency operations from food safety inspections to National Parks to IRS processing were suspended; every parliamentary democracy with a separation-of-powers structure includes automatic funding continuity provisions; government shutdowns are a uniquely American legislative dysfunction; the shutdown mechanism has been deliberately weaponized as political leverage in appropriations disputes -- in 2018-2019 it was used to demand border wall funding that had been separately rejected by Congress. Enforcement mechanisms: Automatic trigger -- no legislative action required for the CR to take effect, removing the mechanism as leverage; private right of action for harmed employees and contractors -- creates individual plaintiffs with standing to seek injunctive relief against shutdown enforcement; OMB dashboard -- creates real-time public accountability for appropriations status; inflation adjustment -- prevents deliberate inaction from being used as a slow defunding mechanism. PolicyOS compliance: KERN-0001 (ensuring continuous government operations is a floor requirement for any functioning federal regulatory and service state); KERN-0004 (automatic CRs ensure the democratically enacted programs and agencies Congress funded the prior year continue to operate without requiring a hostage-taking negotiation every fiscal year -- this is a basic function of constitutional governance). Adversarial review: Gap -- automatic CRs at prior-year funding levels freeze agency budgets in place during periods of congressional inaction, which could be used by a hostile Congress that refuses to pass new appropriations as an indefinite funding cap on programs it opposes; the CPI inflation adjustment helps but doesn't address targeted starvation of specific programs. Loophole -- the statute could be drafted to not apply to "new" programs enacted after the prior fiscal year, creating an incentive to characterize existing programs as "new" to deprive them of automatic CR protection; the statute must specify that all programs with a prior-year appropriation, regardless of when enacted, are covered. Unintended consequence -- automatic CRs could reduce Congress's sense of urgency about completing the appropriations process on time, leading to permanent reliance on automatic CRs and loss of the annual appropriations review function; a penalty mechanism (e.g., reduced congressional office budgets during automatic CR periods) could preserve the incentive to complete the regular appropriations process. Abuse path -- a future president could declare a shutdown emergency and attempt to impound the automatic CR funds using Impoundment Control Act defiance, effectively vetoing the automatic mechanism through executive unilateralism; the statute must specify that automatic CR funds may not be impounded and that impoundment attempts are judicially reviewable on an expedited basis.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-PROS-0007">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-PROS-0007</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Mandatory 72-hour reading rule, all legislation must be publicly available in final form for at least 72 hours before any floor vote; amendments require 24 hours; waiver requires a recorded 2/3 supermajority</p><p class="rule-plain">Every bill must be posted online in its final form at least 72 hours before any vote, giving members of Congress and the public time to read it.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">A statutory 72-hour reading rule that cannot be waived by unilateral leadership action must be enacted, providing: (1) no bill, joint resolution, or conference report may be called for a final vote in either chamber until its final, enrolled text has been continuously available in the official publicly accessible congressional document repository for at least 72 consecutive hours; (2) any amendment offered to a bill before either chamber must be published in the Congressional Record and in the public repository at least 24 consecutive hours before a vote on that amendment; (3) the 72-hour requirement may be waived only by a recorded vote of 2/3 of the full chamber membership, not merely a quorum present, declaring a specified emergency; (4) all committee reports, Congressional Budget Office cost estimates, and other formal analyses must be published simultaneously with and linked to the bill text in the public repository; (5) all documents must be available in open, machine-readable formats downloadable by any member of the public without charge, registration, or tracking; and (6) any member of the public must have standing in federal district court to seek declaratory and injunctive relief against a floor vote called in violation of this requirement, with courts authorized to enjoin certification of any bill passed in deliberate violation pending compliance.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Legal basis: Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017, Pub. L. No. 115-97, 131 Stat. 2054 (the 2017 TCJA was voted on by the Senate hours after handwritten changes appeared in the margins of circulated draft pages -- members, their staff, and the public were given no meaningful time to evaluate late-night amendments before the final vote); U.S. Const. art. I, § 5 (each chamber determines its own rules of proceedings -- the 72-hour statutory requirement operates within this authority); 5 U.S.C. § 552 (Freedom of Information Act, establishing the principle of public access to government records -- a 72-hour rule is consistent with this underlying principle and extends it to legislative process); Rules of the House of Representatives, Rule XIII (existing House rules on committee reports -- the 72-hour rule supplements and strengthens these requirements). Empirical evidence: Congress routinely passes legislation whose text members have not read; the TCJA vote is the clearest modern example of a $1.5 trillion restructuring enacted hours after the final text was circulated with handwritten margin notes; leadership scheduling control is routinely used as leverage, bringing major legislation to the floor on compressed timelines that prevent members from evaluating, amending, or publicly explaining what they are voting on; the failure to allow public reading time makes meaningful constituent engagement before votes impossible. Enforcement mechanisms: Standing for members of the public to seek injunctive relief in federal court -- creates enforceable judicial backstop against leadership rule violations; 2/3 full-chamber vote required for emergency waiver -- prevents leadership from waiving unilaterally; real-time public repository requirement -- provides evidence base for enforcement challenges; machine-readable open formats -- enables civil society monitoring and rapid automated compliance checking. PolicyOS compliance: KERN-0004 (democratic accountability requires that legislation be publicly readable before votes -- secret or unreadable legislation is incompatible with self-governance); DEMO-0001 (public access to final text 72 hours before vote enables constituent engagement with their representatives before the vote occurs, a basic function of representative democracy). Adversarial review: Gap -- the 72-hour clock could be gamed by releasing a "final" text that is then amended in technical corrections bills or reconciliation procedures hours before the actual operative vote, satisfying the letter of the rule while defeating its purpose; the rule must specify that any amendment, technical correction, or substitute text resets the 72-hour clock. Loophole -- leadership could define "final, enrolled text" narrowly to refer to the base text only, allowing late amendments to be characterized as procedural modifications not subject to the 72-hour window; the rule must explicitly include all amendments, substitute amendments, conference report modifications, and manager's amendments within the clock-reset requirement. Unintended consequence -- a 72-hour mandatory minimum could create an incentive for leadership to rush legislation to the floor exactly at the 72-hour mark rather than allowing more deliberation, treating the minimum as a maximum; the rule must be understood as a floor, not a ceiling, and committee procedures encouraging extended deliberation should be preserved. Abuse path -- in a genuine emergency (pandemic, financial crisis, imminent military threat), a 2/3 supermajority waiver requirement could become itself a leverage point for a minority to block emergency legislation unless its priorities are included; the emergency waiver threshold must be set with this risk in mind and accompanied by narrow, time-limited emergency waiver language that sunsets automatically.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="policy-family" id="fam-leg-exe">
<div class="family-header">
<span class="family-code">LEG</span>
<span class="family-title">EXE: Legislative-Executive Relationship</span>
<span class="family-count">1/1 active</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-grid">
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-EXES-0001">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-EXES-0001</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Legislature may select or remove head of government</p><p class="rule-plain">Congress could have the power to select the head of government (like a prime minister) and remove them through a no-confidence vote, rather than having a separately elected president.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">The legislature may play a role in selecting, confirming, or removing the head of government to ensure alignment between lawmaking and execution.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Legislative involvement in selecting or removing the executive ensures alignment between the lawmaking and executive functions. This addresses the structural separation that can produce divided-government paralysis.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="policy-family" id="fam-leg-ovr">
<div class="family-header">
<span class="family-code">LEG</span>
<span class="family-title">OVR: Congressional Oversight</span>
<span class="family-count">2/2 active</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-grid">
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-OVRG-0001">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-OVRG-0001</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Congress must have strong oversight and enforcement powers</p><p class="rule-plain">Congress must have strong powers to investigate and check the executive branch, including the ability to demand documents and testimony with real enforcement mechanisms.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Congress must have strong investigatory, oversight, and enforcement powers over executive offices and agencies.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Strong investigatory, oversight, and enforcement authority over executive offices is the constitutional mechanism for preventing executive overreach. Without these powers, the separation of powers becomes functionally asymmetric.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-OVRG-0002">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-OVRG-0002</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Oversight cannot be blocked by executive privilege or partisanship</p><p class="rule-plain">The president cannot use executive privilege or other excuses to block legitimate congressional oversight, and partisan politics cannot prevent investigations from happening.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Legislative oversight may not be weakened through procedural obstruction, executive privilege abuse, or partisan shielding.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Procedural obstruction, executive privilege abuse, and partisan shielding are the primary mechanisms by which oversight has been weakened in practice. This rule establishes that effective oversight is a right, not merely an aspiration.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="policy-family" id="fam-leg-dmj">
<div class="family-header">
<span class="family-code">LEG</span>
<span class="family-title">DMJ: Democratic Majority Protection</span>
<span class="family-count">2/2 active</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-grid">
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-DMJS-0001">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-DMJS-0001</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Structural minority rule over national policy is prohibited</p><p class="rule-plain">No system can be allowed where a minority of voters consistently controls national policy decisions, whether through the Senate, Electoral College, or gerrymandered districts.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Legislative systems must prevent structural minority rule where a minority of the population can consistently control or block national policy.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Where a minority population can consistently control or block national policy, the legislature has ceased to function as a democratic institution. This rule establishes that structural minority rule is a policy failure, not a design feature.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-DMJS-0002">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-DMJS-0002</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Representational systems require periodic democratic review</p><p class="rule-plain">Systems for electing representatives and making laws must be regularly reviewed to ensure they still reflect democratic principles and don't give unfair advantages to any group.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Electoral and representational systems must be periodically reviewed and adjusted to maintain democratic legitimacy.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Democratic legitimacy cannot be established once and then frozen; population shifts and structural changes require periodic reassessment. Regular review ensures that representational systems maintain their democratic basis over time.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="policy-family" id="fam-leg-db">
<div class="family-header">
<span class="family-code">LEG</span>
<span class="family-title">DB: Public Law Database</span>
<span class="family-count">4/4 active</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-grid">
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-DBAS-0001">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-DBAS-0001</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Establish searchable public federal law database</p><p class="rule-plain">The federal government must create a free online database where anyone can search and read all federal laws in one place, not scattered across different websites.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Establish a public federal law database containing the full text, plain-language summaries, legislative context, amendment history, major legal interpretations, and enforcement status of federal laws.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">A comprehensive, searchable public database of federal law with plain-language summaries and amendment history would dramatically improve legislative accountability and public understanding. This addresses the opacity that contributes to legislative dysfunction.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-DBAS-0002">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-DBAS-0002</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Database includes judicial opinions and agency interpretations</p><p class="rule-plain">The law database must also include court decisions and government agency interpretations so people can understand what laws actually mean in practice.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">The public law database should include major judicial opinions, agency interpretations, legislative history summaries, and public-facing explanatory material for each law.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Including major interpretive materials alongside statutory text gives the public a complete picture of what the law actually means in practice. Law divorced from its interpretations is incomplete and potentially misleading.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-DBAS-0003">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-DBAS-0003</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Database allows structured public comment and annotation</p><p class="rule-plain">The database should let the public comment on laws and flag sections that are confusing or problematic, helping lawmakers identify what needs fixing.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">The public law database should allow public comment, critique, and annotated public input, clearly separated from official legal materials.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Public comment and annotation capabilities transform a static repository into a living accountability mechanism. Clear separation from official materials ensures public input does not contaminate the authoritative legal record.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-DBAS-0004">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-DBAS-0004</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Law database must be free, searchable, and accessible</p><p class="rule-plain">The federal law database must be completely free to access, easy to search, and work well on phones and computers so every American can look up the law.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">The public law database must be free, searchable, versioned, and accessible to the public without subscription barriers.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Accessibility is prerequisite for the database's democratic function. Subscription barriers would recreate the access inequality the database is designed to address.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="policy-family" id="fam-leg-drf">
<div class="family-header">
<span class="family-code">LEG</span>
<span class="family-title">DRF: Legislative Drafting Standards</span>
<span class="family-count">6/6 active</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-grid">
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-DRFS-0001">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-DRFS-0001</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Binding drafting standards required for all new federal laws</p><p class="rule-plain">Congress must follow mandatory writing standards when creating new laws to make them clearer, more consistent, and harder to exploit through loopholes.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">A constitutional amendment or equivalent binding rule should establish drafting standards for all new federal laws.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Constitutional or equivalent binding drafting standards would ensure that laws are consistently structured, clear, and purposeful. Voluntary standards have proven insufficient to prevent the complexity and opacity that enables legal exploitation.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-DRFS-0002">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-DRFS-0002</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Each new law requires plain-language statement of purpose</p><p class="rule-plain">Every new law must include a plain-language statement at the beginning explaining what problem it's trying to solve and what it's supposed to accomplish.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Every new law must include a plain-language statement of intent, purpose, and context.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Requiring a plain-language statement of intent for every new law creates both accountability and interpretive clarity. Ambiguous purpose statements are the primary source of exploit-enabling legal ambiguity.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-DRFS-0003">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-DRFS-0003</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Large sections require plain-language summaries</p><p class="rule-plain">Complex sections of laws must include plain-language summaries so ordinary people can understand what the law does without needing a lawyer.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Large sections, subsections, and amendments must include plain-language summaries and stated intent.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Requiring plain-language summaries for major sections and amendments makes complex legislation accessible to those it governs. This reduces the information asymmetry between sophisticated legal actors and the general public.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-DRFS-0004">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-DRFS-0004</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Each provision must be relevant to the law's stated purpose</p><p class="rule-plain">Every part of a law must be relevant to its stated purpose. Lawmakers cannot hide unrelated provisions in bills to sneak them through.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Each provision of a law must be clearly relevant to the purpose and scope of that law.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Limiting provisions to matters relevant to the law's stated purpose would eliminate legislative riders that attach unrelated policy to must-pass legislation. This is a basic coherence requirement that prevents policy laundering.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-DRFS-0005">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-DRFS-0005</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Laws reviewed for loopholes and exploit paths before passage</p><p class="rule-plain">Before passing a new law, Congress must review it to identify and close loopholes that could be used to undermine its purpose.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Proposed laws must be reviewed for loopholes, gaps, conflicts with existing law, and likely exploit paths before passage.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Pre-passage review for loopholes, gaps, and exploit paths would catch many of the structural vulnerabilities that sophisticated actors exploit after enactment. This shifts the burden of anticipating misuse from courts and agencies to the legislature.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-DRFS-0006">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-DRFS-0006</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Conflicts with existing law reconciled before enactment</p><p class="rule-plain">Before enacting a new law, Congress must identify any conflicts with existing laws and fix them, preventing contradictory rules that confuse people.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Conflicts between proposed laws and existing laws must be reconciled before enactment rather than left for courts or agencies to resolve later.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Requiring conflict reconciliation before enactment prevents the legal ambiguity that results when new laws contradict existing ones. Leaving such conflicts to courts and agencies creates expensive and unpredictable outcomes.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="policy-family" id="fam-leg-rev">
<div class="family-header">
<span class="family-code">LEG</span>
<span class="family-title">REV: Legislative Review</span>
<span class="family-count">3/3 active</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-grid">
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-REVS-0001">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-REVS-0001</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Permanent body annually reviews federal laws for obsolescence</p><p class="rule-plain">A permanent office must review federal laws every year to find outdated or unnecessary ones that should be repealed or updated.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Establish a permanent independent federal review body that annually reviews federal laws for outdated, unenforced, contradictory, obsolete, or practically unenforceable language.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">An independent permanent review body with annual reporting requirements would provide systematic identification of outdated, contradictory, and unenforceable laws. The accumulation of dead-letter law creates complexity and the potential for selective enforcement.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-REVS-0002">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-REVS-0002</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Review body recommends repeal, consolidation, or modernization</p><p class="rule-plain">The law review office must recommend which obsolete laws should be repealed, which should be combined, and which should be modernized to match current needs.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">The law-review body should recommend repeal, consolidation, modernization, or clarification of obsolete or nonfunctional federal laws.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Review without recommendation is insufficient; the body must produce actionable proposals for Congress to consider. Consolidation of redundant laws and repeal of obsolete ones would reduce complexity and improve enforceability.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-REVS-0003">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-REVS-0003</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Review process includes public reporting and cleanup packages</p><p class="rule-plain">The law review process must include public reports showing what was found, and Congress must vote on cleanup packages to remove or fix outdated laws.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">The law-review process must include public reporting, prioritization criteria, and regular submission of recommended cleanup packages to Congress.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Public reporting on law review findings creates accountability and enables public participation. Regular submission of cleanup packages to Congress provides a structured mechanism for acting on review recommendations.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="policy-family" id="fam-leg-rpl">
<div class="family-header">
<span class="family-code">LEG</span>
<span class="family-title">RPL: Repeal</span>
<span class="family-count">2/2 active</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-grid">
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-RPLS-0001">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-RPLS-0001</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Repeal Alien Enemies Act and related emergency abuse frameworks</p><p class="rule-plain">The Alien Enemies Act, which allows the president to detain or deport people based on nationality during wartime, must be repealed along with similar laws that enable emergency power abuse.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Repeal the Alien Enemies Act / Alien Insurrection Act framework and related emergency-authority structures that enable abuse against non-citizens through vague wartime or insurrection logic.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">The Alien Enemies Act and related emergency-authority structures have enabled documented abuse against non-citizens through vague wartime logic. Repeal removes the legal infrastructure for this category of abuse before it can be further exploited.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-RPLS-0002">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-RPLS-0002</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Repeal Comstock Act and similar archaic morality laws</p><p class="rule-plain">The Comstock Act, a 19th-century law that criminalized mailing birth control information, and similar outdated morality laws must be fully repealed.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Repeal the Comstock Act and any surviving federal provisions that can be used to suppress lawful healthcare, reproductive autonomy, or protected materials through archaic morality law.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">The Comstock Act enables suppression of lawful healthcare and protected materials through nineteenth-century morality law that has been selectively revived. Repeal eliminates a documented vector for reproductive healthcare interference.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="policy-family" id="fam-bba">
<div class="family-header">
<span class="family-code">LEG</span>
<span class="family-title">BBA: Balanced Budget Amendment Opposition</span>
<span class="family-count">0/2 active</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-grid">
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-BBAS-0001">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-BBAS-0001</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Oppose constitutional balanced budget amendment as economically harmful</p><p class="rule-plain">A constitutional amendment requiring a balanced federal budget every year is a bad idea that would harm the economy during recessions and must be opposed.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Congress must not pass, and states must not ratify, a constitutional amendment requiring a balanced federal budget in any form that eliminates or severely constrains deficit spending. Balanced budget requirements in constitutional form are specifically rejected because they would force pro-cyclical fiscal policy, requiring spending cuts or tax increases precisely during recessions when the economy most needs countercyclical stimulus, structurally worsening economic downturns and producing outcomes worse than the problem they purport to solve.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Economic research across the mainstream spectrum, including from the Economic Policy Institute, the Center on Budget and Policy Priorities, and mainstream academic economists, consistently concludes that a constitutional balanced budget amendment would be severely harmful.<sup><a href="#fn5" id="ref5">[5]</a></sup> During recessions, tax revenues fall and safety net spending rises automatically; a hard balanced budget requirement would force Congress to cut programs or raise taxes at the worst possible moment, deepening the recession. No major developed economy has a constitutional requirement that eliminates countercyclical flexibility. The goal of fiscal sustainability is legitimate; achieving it through a constitutional straitjacket is not. [Adversarial review per PAOS-TEST-0008] The platform's opposition to all forms of BBA does not specifically engage with variants that include emergency override clauses, supermajority override provisions, or capital vs. operating budget distinctions, proponents will argue these variants address the pro-cyclical problem; the rule should explain why such variants are also rejected. Opposing a BBA without pairing it with a credible statutory fiscal sustainability framework (addressed in LEGL-BBAS-0002) is politically vulnerable to the charge of advocating unlimited deficits; these two cards must be read and presented together. The argument that no major developed economy has a constitutional balanced budget requirement is accurate for national governments but ignores that 49 U.S. states operate under statutory or constitutional balanced budget requirements, critics will cite state-level experience as evidence of feasibility; the platform should directly address the federal-versus-state distinction.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-BBAS-0002">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-BBAS-0002</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Establish a statutory long-term fiscal sustainability framework, not a constitutional amendment</p><p class="rule-plain">Congress should establish a regular law (not a constitutional amendment) that sets long-term fiscal goals and budget guidelines while allowing flexibility during economic downturns.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">The correct approach to long-term fiscal sustainability is a statutory framework, not a constitutional amendment, that establishes debt-to-GDP targets, automatic stabilizer protections that exempt recession-period spending, transparent long-term budget projections, and a bipartisan joint committee with mandatory reporting on fiscal sustainability. Statutory frameworks can be adjusted as economic conditions change; constitutional constraints cannot. The framework must distinguish between capital investment spending and operating deficits.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">The Congressional Budget Office already provides statutory-mandate long-term fiscal projections; expanding and improving that framework provides the transparency value of a balanced budget requirement without the economic harm. Countries that adopted rules-based fiscal frameworks after economic crises generally did so through statute rather than constitutional amendment, precisely because statutory rules can be adjusted in genuine emergencies while maintaining credibility through predictability and built-in enforcement mechanisms. [Adversarial review per PAOS-TEST-0008] A statutory fiscal sustainability framework can be suspended or repealed by a simple majority, the same Congress that finds the rules inconvenient can abolish them, undermining long-term credibility relative to a constitutional mechanism; the rule should specify whether any supermajority threshold is required to waive or repeal the framework. The "automatic stabilizer protections exempting recession-period spending" require a precise statutory definition of "recession" for triggering purposes; if the definition is left to political discretion, Congress can perpetually claim emergency conditions to avoid the framework's constraints. A bipartisan joint committee on fiscal sustainability has no track record of success in the U.S. context, the Joint Select Committee on Deficit Reduction created by the Budget Control Act of 2011 failed entirely to reach agreement, and the rule should address what happens if the committee deadlocks. The distinction between capital investment spending and operating deficits, while economically sound, requires rigorous implementation rules to prevent reclassification of routine operating expenditures as "investment" to escape framework constraints.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="policy-family" id="fam-cap">
<div class="family-header">
<span class="family-code">LEG</span>
<span class="family-title">CAP: Congressional Capacity and Staffing</span>
<span class="family-count">0/3 active</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-grid">
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-CAPS-0001">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-CAPS-0001</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Substantially increase congressional staff salaries and total staff capacity</p><p class="rule-plain">Congressional staff must be paid significantly more and Congress must hire more staff overall so members have the expertise needed to understand complex issues and write good laws.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Congress must substantially increase staff compensation and total staffing levels for member offices, committees, and the House and Senate as institutions. Staff salaries must be benchmarked against equivalent private-sector expertise, not capped at civil service grades that make congressional employment a temporary stepping stone to lobbying. Restoring the Office of Technology Assessment and expanding CRS, CBO, and GAO capacity must be funded as institutional priorities, not as discretionary line items subject to partisan political pressure.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Research by Lee Drutman and the Congressional Management Foundation documents that congressional staff resources have declined significantly in real terms since the 1970s while the complexity of the legislative environment has grown dramatically.<sup><a href="#fn6" id="ref6">[6]</a></sup> The result is a systematic expertise deficit: members and staff must rely on lobbyists and executive branch officials for technical knowledge Congress once generated internally. Low salaries create a revolving door into lobbying: staff leave for industry because industry can pay three to five times the congressional salary for the same expertise. [Adversarial review per PAOS-TEST-0008] Benchmarking congressional staff salaries against "equivalent private-sector expertise" is analytically difficult because the skills most valued in government, political judgment, coalition-building, legislative procedure, are not precisely equivalent to private-sector roles; market rates may reflect lobbying demand for government-connected skills rather than genuine comparable work value. Higher congressional salaries could paradoxically increase the revolving door problem by making congressional employment more attractive as a credentialing step before entering lobbying, the "congressional alumni" brand may become more, not less, commercially valuable if staff are seen as better trained and compensated. Protecting CRS, CBO, and GAO budgets from partisan appropriations pressure requires structural insulation that simple authorization language cannot guarantee; the appropriations committees whose chairs benefit from the current information asymmetry have strong institutional incentives to resist adequate funding for independent analysis. The rule should specify a salary floor or parity target; without a defined benchmark, "substantially increase" is an unenforceable aspiration.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-CAPS-0002">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-CAPS-0002</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Restore the Office of Technology Assessment with independent mandate</p><p class="rule-plain">The Office of Technology Assessment, which provided Congress with independent scientific and technical advice until it was closed in 1995, must be reopened with proper funding.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">The Office of Technology Assessment, abolished in 1995, must be reestablished as a permanent nonpartisan office of Congress with a budget adequate to provide rigorous independent technical analysis of science, technology, and emerging policy issues. OTA must be governed by a bipartisan board, publish all major assessments publicly, and be insulated from political pressure by removing its budget from the annual appropriations process subject to majority vote.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">OTA was abolished in 1995 as part of the "Contract with America" budget cuts. In its 23-year history it produced over 750 major assessments on issues from telecommunications to climate change that were authoritative precisely because they were independent of both partisan politics and industry lobbying. In its absence, Congress has become increasingly dependent on industry-funded analysis and advocacy group research with undisclosed funders. Multiple bipartisan legislative efforts have sought to restore OTA; the obstacle has been political resistance from those who benefit from the current information deficit. [Adversarial review per PAOS-TEST-0008] A bipartisan governing board is structurally prone to deadlock on contested technological issues, climate science, AI risk, pharmaceutical assessment, precisely where independent analysis is most needed and most politically charged; the rule should specify a deadlock resolution mechanism. The requirement to remove OTA's budget from the annual appropriations process subject to majority vote may conflict with the constitutional appropriations power, as Congress cannot bind future Congresses by simple majority rule; a future appropriations majority could simply exclude the OTA line. The original OTA was criticized by some members for assessments that reflected the analytical priorities of the majority; "independence" guaranteed by a bipartisan board does not prevent gradual alignment with congressional majority preferences on politically contested science questions. Without transparent methodology requirements and open public comment processes, OTA assessments conflicting with industry interests will face well-funded credibility attacks from opposition research operations.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-CAPS-0003">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-CAPS-0003</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Mandatory member schedule, minimum days in session with committee attendance requirements</p><p class="rule-plain">Members of Congress must be required to spend a minimum number of days in session and attending committee meetings, ending the practice of constant fundraising trips.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">The House and Senate must adopt rules requiring minimum days in session per year, minimum committee attendance requirements for members, and a schedule that concentrates legislative work in Washington rather than fragmenting it around fundraising travel. Members who fail to meet attendance thresholds without documented cause must have that absence entered in the public record as part of their official voting record. Congress must be in session long enough to conduct hearings, mark up legislation, and exercise oversight.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">The congressional legislative calendar has contracted significantly over the past three decades. The House typically works a three-day legislative week to accommodate fundraising travel. Committee hearing days have fallen. Shortened schedules reduce time available for genuine deliberation, oversight hearings, and complex legislative drafting, creating more dependence on executive branch drafting assistance and lobbyists who effectively write legislation for members who lack staff capacity to draft it themselves. [Adversarial review per PAOS-TEST-0008] Minimum days-in-session requirements can be gamed by gaveling in for quorum calls and immediately recessing, "pro forma" sessions technically count as legislative days while conducting no business; the rule should specify meaningful activity thresholds, not just calendar presence. Mandatory Washington presence reduces time available for constituency service, town halls, and direct constituent contact; the tradeoff between Washington deliberation and district engagement is not solved by simply requiring more Washington days. Attendance requirements without content requirements create the perverse incentive to show up but do nothing substantive, a member physically present during a ceremonial week is no more effective than one who is absent. The rule does not specify minimum thresholds, session days per year, committee attendance percentage, or hearing count, leaving the standard unenforceable until those numbers are defined through separate rulemaking.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="policy-family" id="fam-lob">
<div class="family-header">
<span class="family-code">LEG</span>
<span class="family-title">LOB: Lobbying Reform and Revolving Door</span>
<span class="family-count">0/4 active</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-grid">
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-LOBS-0001">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-LOBS-0001</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Extend congressional revolving door cooling-off period to five years</p><p class="rule-plain">Members of Congress and senior staff cannot become lobbyists until five years after leaving office, preventing them from immediately cashing in on their government connections.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Former members of Congress and senior congressional staff with meaningful access and influence may not register as lobbyists or engage in lobbying activity within five years of leaving congressional service. The current one- and two-year cooling-off periods are inadequate: relationships, access, and insider knowledge remain highly valuable well beyond two years. The prohibition must cover not only registered lobbying activity but shadow lobbying, consulting, advising, or facilitating lobbying contact, as well as work for foreign principals covered by FARA.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">OpenSecrets tracks hundreds of former members and senior staff who move into lobbying or government affairs roles within months of leaving office.<sup><a href="#fn7" id="ref7">[7]</a></sup> The one-year ban for House members and two-year ban for Senators is routinely avoided by using "strategic advisor" periods before formal registration, or by advising clients on lobbying strategy without personally making direct lobbying contact. Five-year cooling-off periods create a gap wide enough to reduce the commercial value of former-member insider access as a marketable product. [Adversarial review per PAOS-TEST-0008] The prohibition on "shadow lobbying" is difficult to enforce because distinguishing between legitimate strategic consulting and facilitating a lobbying contact requires factual investigation that current enforcement bodies lack the capacity and subpoena authority to conduct. A five-year ban may be sufficiently severe that experienced policy professionals decline congressional service entirely, the opposite of the stated goal of building congressional capacity, because post-service employment options are too restricted. Former members can circumvent the cooling-off by forming "policy research" entities or think tanks that maintain their lobbying relationships as institutional assets while technically complying with the letter of the ban. The rule applies to "senior staff with meaningful access and influence" but does not define the seniority threshold, which risks both over-inclusion of junior staff who lacked material influence and under-inclusion of senior political staff who shaped relationships without formal senior titles.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-LOBS-0002">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-LOBS-0002</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Real-time lobbying disclosure, replace quarterly reports with continuous filing</p><p class="rule-plain">When lobbyists meet with members of Congress, they must report it online within 24 hours instead of quarterly, so the public can see who's influencing lawmakers in real time.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">The Lobbying Disclosure Act (2 U.S.C. §§ 1601 et seq.) must be amended to require real-time disclosure of lobbying contacts: within 48 hours of any in-person or direct communication with a covered official on behalf of a client. Quarterly LD-2 reports must be supplemented by real-time contact logs. Covered communication must include meetings, calls, emails, and written submissions by registered lobbyists and their clients. The database must be publicly searchable in real time.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Current quarterly LDA reporting provides a delayed, aggregated picture of lobbying activity. By the time a quarterly report is filed, the legislation it targeted may already have passed, been defeated, or been modified. Real-time disclosure, the standard already applied to direct campaign contributions, would allow journalists, competitors, and voters to see lobbying pressure as it is applied, creating accountability for both the lobbyist and the official being contacted. The technical infrastructure for real-time disclosure is already available. [Adversarial review per PAOS-TEST-0008] The 48-hour window still allows lobbying contacts to be made, influence applied, and votes taken before the contact is publicly disclosed, particularly in fast-moving legislative situations; a 24-hour or same-day standard may be necessary when votes are scheduled with little notice. Indirect or "grassroots" lobbying, organized public pressure campaigns orchestrated by paid lobbyists but executed through nominally independent constituent communications, is not covered by the LDA at any reporting frequency; well-resourced campaigns may shift toward this channel to avoid real-time disclosure. A "publicly searchable in real time" database requirement does not specify query capability or format standards; data published as bulk XML dumps or non-indexed documents satisfies the letter of the rule while enabling no practical accountability. Coalition lobbying through trade associations or industry groups allows individual companies to benefit from lobbying while their names do not appear in the disclosure record; this structural gap is not addressed by real-time LD-2 reporting.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-LOBS-0003">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-LOBS-0003</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Earmark transparency reform, full disclosure required; outright ban rejected as counterproductive</p><p class="rule-plain">Earmarks (spending directed to specific projects) must be fully disclosed online, including who requested them and why, so voters can see if their representatives are serving special interests.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Congressional earmarks: directed spending provisions in appropriations bills, must be subject to full public disclosure including the requesting member's name, the recipient entity, the amount, the purpose, and any financial interests of the member in the recipient. Earmarks must be submitted at least 30 days before floor consideration to allow scrutiny. Earmarks to private for-profit entities are prohibited; earmarks to nonprofit and government entities are permitted with disclosure. The outright ban on all earmarks is rejected as counterproductive.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Political science research has documented that the 2011 earmark moratorium did not reduce overall spending; it shifted spending decisions to the executive branch and reduced the legislative leverage Congress can use to build coalitions for major legislation. Transparent, disclosed earmarks with conflict-of-interest requirements and public justification are less susceptible to corruption than the alternative: informal telephone calls to agency officials requesting the same spending as an undisclosed executive priority. The solution to earmark abuse is transparency and accountability, not abolition. [Adversarial review per PAOS-TEST-0008] The prohibition on earmarks to "private for-profit entities" can be circumvented by routing projects through nonprofit shell organizations or government-sponsored entities that nominally meet the nonprofit requirement while primarily benefiting private interests controlled by politically connected individuals. The 30-day pre-floor submission window creates a gamesmanship dynamic: members may time requests in waves just at the deadline, and well-organized constituencies in competitive districts are systematically better positioned to mobilize earmark requests than unorganized constituencies in safe seats. The definition of "any financial interests of the member in the recipient" requires a precise statutory definition to capture indirect interests held through family members, investment vehicles, former business associations, and campaign donor relationships. Earmark disclosure requirements do not cap the total volume of earmarks; without spending limits, transparency reform may produce publicly disclosed but still systemically distorted allocation of federal resources toward politically influential applicants.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-LOBS-0004">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-LOBS-0004</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Revolving door extended to executive branch senior officials and independent agency heads</p><p class="rule-plain">The five-year cooling-off period before becoming a lobbyist also applies to senior executive branch officials and independent agency heads, not just Congress members.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Senior executive branch officials, including cabinet secretaries, deputy secretaries, agency heads, and senior White House staff, must be subject to the same five-year cooling-off period from lobbying and foreign agent activity as senior congressional staff. Heads and commissioners of independent regulatory agencies (FCC, FTC, SEC, FERC, and others) must be subject to a five-year ban on working for entities they directly regulated in the two years before leaving office, including as a board member, paid advisor, or consultant.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">The executive branch revolving door is in many respects more consequential than the congressional one, because agencies write rules with the force of law, and former agency officials can be extraordinarily valuable to regulated industries seeking to shape those rules. FCC commissioners who go on to represent telecommunications companies, SEC commissioners who go on to represent financial firms, and FDA officials who go on to represent pharmaceutical companies create conflicts between public service and private reward that the current two-year revolving door ban does not adequately address. [Adversarial review per PAOS-TEST-0008] The "directly regulated in the two years before leaving office" standard for independent agency heads is subject to aggressive narrow interpretation: an official can argue they did not "directly" regulate a specific company even when they led the division responsible for that company's industry, reducing enforcement scope. Stock, option, or deferred compensation arrangements negotiated before departure but vesting after the ban period ends can effectively compensate executives for the cooling-off period without technically violating the restriction. The ban on board membership, paid advising, and consulting may drive post-government employment toward executive officer roles at regulated firms, corporate officers rather than advisors, if the statutory definition does not capture all forms of material compensation for influence. The rule requires separate legal authority to apply to independent agency commissioners, whose tenure protections and independence from executive direction may create enforcement complications that do not arise for ordinary cabinet officers.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="policy-family" id="fam-stk">
<div class="family-header">
<span class="family-code">LEG</span>
<span class="family-title">STK: Congressional Stock Trading and Financial Ethics</span>
<span class="family-count">0/2 active</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-grid">
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-STKS-0001">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-STKS-0001</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Ban on individual stock trading by members of Congress, senior staff, and immediate family</p><p class="rule-plain">Members of Congress, their senior staff, and their immediate families cannot own or trade individual stocks while in office, only broad index funds, to prevent insider trading.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Members of Congress, senior congressional staff with regular access to non-public legislative information, and their spouses and minor children may not purchase or sell individual securities, options, futures, or other financial instruments tied to single companies. All existing holdings must be placed in a qualified blind trust or divested within 180 days of enactment. Investments in broadly diversified index funds and U.S. Treasury securities are permitted. Violations carry criminal penalties under securities law and mandatory forfeiture of profits.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">The STOCK Act (Stop Trading on Congressional Knowledge Act), passed in 2012, requires disclosure of securities transactions within 45 days but does not ban trading. POGO, Business Insider, and multiple news outlets have documented hundreds of members who failed to disclose trades on time, often receiving nominal $200 fines, as well as patterns of members trading in industries they directly oversee through committee assignments. The disclosure requirement without a trading ban is insufficient because it creates the appearance of accountability without preventing the underlying conflict of interest. [Adversarial review per PAOS-TEST-0008] The exemption for "broadly diversified index funds" does not prevent members on sector-specific committees from holding index funds heavily weighted toward the sectors they regulate, a member on the Senate Banking Committee retains meaningful financial exposure to the financial sector through any broad market index. The 180-day divestiture window creates a structured period of insider advantage before the ban takes effect; Congress could limit this risk by prohibiting new purchases in individual securities immediately upon enactment while allowing divestiture time for existing holdings. Enforcement of the spouse and minor children provision requires information-sharing mechanisms with brokerage custodians and the IRS that do not currently exist in the congressional disclosure system; the rule should specify reporting requirements for covered household members. Routing criminal enforcement through DOJ, which has historically declined to investigate or prosecute members of Congress, does not guarantee the independence from political discretion that a genuinely deterrent enforcement regime requires.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-STKS-0002">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-STKS-0002</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Strengthen STOCK Act enforcement, automatic civil penalties and an independent enforcer</p><p class="rule-plain">The STOCK Act, which prohibits insider trading by Congress, must have automatic financial penalties for violations and an independent watchdog to enforce it aggressively.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">STOCK Act disclosure violations must carry automatic civil penalties, not officer-assessed discretionary fines, calculated as a percentage of the undisclosed transaction value, with a minimum floor that creates genuine deterrence regardless of transaction size. Enforcement authority must be vested in the independent Office of Congressional Ethics (or its successor) rather than the House Ethics Committee, which has a documented history of failing to act on violations. The OCE must be able to refer willful violations directly to DOJ without requiring committee approval.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">The existing $200 fine for late STOCK Act disclosure is widely recognized as inadequate, less than the cost of a parking ticket for members whose transactions regularly involve hundreds of thousands of dollars. News outlets including Business Insider and Quartz have documented that dozens of members file late disclosures routinely, treating the fine as an acceptable compliance cost. The House Ethics Committee's structural weakness, partisan composition and history of inaction, means that self-policing under the current system does not work. [Adversarial review per PAOS-TEST-0008] OCE is an advisory body with referral authority but no final enforcement power; strengthening OCE referral authority does not fix the ultimate enforcement failure unless the House Ethics Committee's composition and process are also reformed, the rule should address both sides of the referral chain. Automatic civil penalties calculated as a percentage of transaction value have a structural problem: a percentage that deters modest-scale violations is trivially affordable for large transactions if the rate is too low, while a high rate may produce disproportionate results for minor administrative errors; a well-designed schedule requires both a minimum floor and a graduated rate. The rule does not address enforcement against senators, who fall under the Senate Ethics Committee with different procedures; without parallel Senate provisions, parity of deterrence is not guaranteed. OCE lacks subpoena power for financial records, meaning its factual investigation must rely primarily on the member's own disclosures; this limits the evidentiary record available to support a DOJ prosecution for willful violations.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="policy-family" id="fam-com">
<div class="family-header">
<span class="family-code">LEG</span>
<span class="family-title">COM: Committee Reform</span>
<span class="family-count">0/2 active</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-grid">
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-COMS-0001">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-COMS-0001</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Replace seniority-only committee assignments with merit and expertise criteria</p><p class="rule-plain">Congressional committee assignments should be based on members' expertise and qualifications, not just how long they've been in Congress.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Committee chair and ranking member positions must be determined through a process that weighs demonstrated subject matter expertise, attendance record, and peer review, not solely seniority. Seniority may be one factor but may not be the sole determining factor. Committee assignments for new members must consider relevant professional background and prior expertise. The goal is to ensure that committees overseeing technical areas, finance, healthcare, technology, environment, national security, include members with genuine knowledge of those fields.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">The seniority system produces chairmanships based on longevity rather than competence, and has historically produced committees chaired by members with no substantive expertise in the area they oversee. This exacerbates the congressional capacity problem: if neither members nor staff have adequate subject-matter expertise, and the committee structure rewards attendance over knowledge, the informational advantage of well-funded lobbyists and executive branch agencies is maximized. Expertise-weighted assignment does not eliminate seniority; it adds competence as a required criterion alongside it. [Adversarial review per PAOS-TEST-0008] The "peer review" component is undefined: if peers means fellow committee members, they may have self-interested reasons to exclude expert competitors; if peers means outside experts, the rule requires an independent evaluation process whose neutrality and accountability are not specified. Defining "demonstrated subject matter expertise" risks privileging academic credentialing and professional certification over forms of experiential knowledge, as a farmer, nurse, small business owner, or tradesperson, that are legitimately relevant to committee oversight of those sectors. Party leadership retains formal authority over committee assignments in both chambers; any rule constraining that authority requires leadership buy-in to function, and leadership has historically resisted constraints on committee assignments as a core party discipline tool. The rule applies to chairs and ranking members but not to ordinary committee membership, where seniority still drives access to desirable committees and the related fundraising opportunities.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-COMS-0002">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-COMS-0002</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Restore committee markup authority, prohibit floor consideration of bills bypassing committee process</p><p class="rule-plain">Bills must go through proper committee review and markup before reaching the floor. Leaders cannot bring bills to a vote that committees haven't reviewed.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">No bill may be considered by the full House or Senate unless it has received at least one public committee hearing and been voted out of the relevant committee of jurisdiction, unless waived by a two-thirds supermajority vote. The practice of bypassing committee consideration through leadership-drafted omnibus bills, continuing resolutions embedding new law, and leadership-controlled floor scheduling that substitutes leadership preference for committee process undermines the deliberative function that committees were designed to serve.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Congressional scholars including Norman Ornstein have documented the steady decline of the committee system as a deliberative body over the past 30 years, replaced by increasingly centralized leadership control. This decline produces less member expertise development, less public deliberation, and reduced ability for minority members to amend or scrutinize legislation. Committee deliberation is not inefficiency; it is the process by which legislation is made to work, by which errors are found, and by which the public can see what is being proposed and why. [Adversarial review per PAOS-TEST-0008] The two-thirds supermajority waiver preserves the ability of a large majority to bypass committee entirely, in a highly partisan environment where one party controls two-thirds of a chamber, the committee process protection is effectively optional when leadership wants to move quickly. The "at least one public committee hearing" requirement can be satisfied by a perfunctory one-hour hearing with no witnesses from affected communities, minimal minority participation, and no substantive staff analysis, meeting the letter while defeating the purpose. Emergency legislation, disaster relief, government funding gaps, national security responses, genuinely requires the ability to move quickly without a full committee process, but the two-thirds waiver threshold may be unreachable for emergency situations requiring fast action by a narrower majority. Committee chairs hostile to a bill they are compelled to consider can structure the markup process to ensure failure: scheduling votes when supporters are absent, limiting amendment opportunities, or using procedural tools to table the bill after satisfying the hearing requirement.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-COMS-0003">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-COMS-0003</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Committee chair term limits, maximum six consecutive years in any single chairmanship</p><p class="rule-plain">Committee chairs can serve a maximum of six consecutive years in that position, preventing them from building unchecked personal power over specific policy areas.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">No member of Congress may serve as chair or ranking member of the same standing committee for more than six consecutive years (three two-year terms in the House; one six-year term in the Senate). After the term limit is reached, the member may serve on the committee in a non-leadership capacity but may not chair or rank that same committee again for at least one full Congress. Term limits apply to full committee chairs and ranking members but not to subcommittee chairs, which may be rotated more frequently at the chamber's discretion.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Committee chair seniority produces long-serving chairs with deeply entrenched relationships with the industries and agencies they oversee, relationships that can shade from expertise into capture. The Senate Republican Conference has imposed its own internal six-year term limit on committee chairs since 1995; House Republicans imposed a similar rule that was subsequently weakened through waivers. Codifying term limits as a standing rule eliminates the waiver problem and applies the same accountability standard to both parties and both chambers. [Adversarial review per PAOS-TEST-0008] The "one full Congress" waiting period between successive chair terms is short enough that a member can rotate off a chairmanship for two years and return with renewed institutional relationships and the same accumulated subject-matter knowledge, substantially reducing the term limit's effectiveness at preventing entrenchment. State legislative experience with leadership term limits documents that when chairs rotate, institutional power can shift toward executive branch agencies and professional lobbyists who retain continuity that rotating members lack, the same dynamic risk applies to federal committee chairs and must be addressed through parallel staff capacity investment. The rule applies only to full committee chairs and ranking members, not to subcommittee chairs, who often manage the detailed jurisdiction of a committee area and can develop relationships equivalent in depth to those of a full chair. Members reaching the six-year limit on one committee can transfer to a closely related committee and effectively continue overseeing the same policy area and the same regulated industries under a new title.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="policy-family" id="fam-filb">
<div class="family-header">
<span class="family-code">LEG</span>
<span class="family-title">FILB: Filibuster Reform</span>
<span class="family-count">0/2 active</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-grid">
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-FILB-0001">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-FILB-0001</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Senators Must Speak Continuously to Maintain a Filibuster; Silent Filibuster Is Abolished</p><p class="rule-plain">If senators want to filibuster a bill, they must actually stand and speak continuously on the Senate floor. Silent filibusters, where they just threaten to block without speaking, are prohibited.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">The Senate must amend its rules to require that any senator seeking to delay or block a vote on legislation must speak continuously and remain present on the Senate floor for the duration of the delay; any pause in debate, absence from the floor, or failure to maintain continuous speech ends the filibuster and permits a majority vote to proceed. The silent or "gentlemen's agreement" filibuster, in which legislation is blocked by merely threatening a filibuster without any floor presence, is abolished. Cloture may be invoked by a simple majority after 24 hours of continuous debate. Senate rules changes may be adopted by a simple majority at the beginning of each new Congress.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Legal basis: U.S. Const. art. I, § 5 (each chamber determines its own rules of proceedings by majority vote -- the filibuster is not constitutionally required and may be modified by a simple majority Senate rule change); Senate Rule XXII (the current cloture rule requiring 60 votes -- changeable by majority vote using the "nuclear option" or at the start of a new Congress); Jefferson's Manual of Parliamentary Practice (the original Senate debate rules contemplated continuous floor presence, not the silent filibuster created by the 1970s rule changes); Koger, G. (2010). Filibustering: A political history of obstruction in the House and Senate. University of Chicago Press (documenting how the silent filibuster emerged from rule changes in the 1970s and is not the historical norm); Talking Filibuster Act of 2021, S. 604, 117th Cong. (2021) (introduced as standalone legislation -- confirming the feasibility of the specific reform). Empirical evidence: The modern silent filibuster was created by Senate rule changes in the 1970s that allowed senators to filibuster without holding the floor -- the talking filibuster was the historical norm from the founding through the mid-twentieth century; the filibuster has been used more than 300 times in recent Congresses, the majority as procedural holds without any floor debate; the Senate has already eliminated the filibuster for executive nominations (2013) and Supreme Court nominations (2017) using the simple majority procedure available for this reform; the silent filibuster allows 41 senators to block legislation indefinitely without any public accountability for their opposition. Enforcement mechanisms: Continuous speech and floor presence requirement -- any pause automatically ends the filibuster, eliminating the procedural hold mechanism; simple majority cloture after 24 hours -- creates a defined endpoint that is enforceable by the majority; simple majority rule change at start of Congress -- establishes the reform without requiring a 60-vote threshold for its own adoption. PolicyOS compliance: KERN-0004 (the silent filibuster allows a minority to veto majority legislative will without accountability -- the talking filibuster restores the democratic accountability function while preserving the deliberative function); DEMO-0001 (requiring senators to speak publicly about why they oppose legislation creates accountability to their constituents for obstruction). Adversarial review: Gap -- the talking filibuster can still be used to permanently block legislation if a party with 41 or more senators is willing to staff floor shifts continuously; a sufficiently motivated minority with enough members can sustain indefinite floor presence; the reform significantly raises the cost of obstruction but does not eliminate it for a determined minority. Loophole -- senators could defeat the continuous-speech requirement by staging elaborate "read-ins" of unrelated documents, phone books, or other filibuster-by-attrition tactics that technically constitute "speech" while providing no deliberative content; the rule should specify that speech must be germane to the legislation being delayed or be ruled out of order by the presiding officer. Unintended consequence -- the talking filibuster could create physical hardship (health issues, exhaustion) for senators with disabilities or health conditions who oppose legislation; accessibility accommodations for floor presence requirements must be specified without creating an exception large enough to recreate the silent filibuster. Abuse path -- a Senate majority could wait until a senator must physically leave the floor for a medical or family emergency and immediately call a vote -- the rule must specify a minimum notice period (e.g., 30 minutes) before a vote may be called after a senator yields the floor, to prevent ambush voting against senators who are physically unable to return immediately.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-FILB-0002">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-FILB-0002</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Voting Rights, Civil Rights, and Constitutional Amendment Legislation Are Not Subject to Filibuster</p><p class="rule-plain">Bills that protect voting rights, civil rights, or propose constitutional amendments cannot be filibustered and require only a simple majority to pass.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">The Senate must establish a categorical exception to cloture requirements for: legislation restoring or expanding voting rights; legislation implementing rights guaranteed by the Constitution or its amendments; anti-corruption and campaign finance legislation; and judicial or executive nominations. These categories of legislation may proceed to a vote by simple majority after a maximum of 20 hours of debate. The Vice President, as President of the Senate, has the authority to rule filibuster tactics out of order for these categories; such rulings may be sustained by a simple majority vote. Congress must codify these exceptions by statute to prevent reversal by Senate rule changes alone.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Legal basis: U.S. Const. art. I, § 5 (each chamber may determine its own rules -- categorical cloture exceptions can be adopted by majority Senate rule change at the start of any Congress); U.S. Const. art. I, § 3, cl. 4 (the Vice President presides over the Senate and has authority as presiding officer to rule on points of order and parliamentary questions -- the basis for rulings that filibuster tactics are out of order for specified categories); John R. Lewis Voting Rights Advancement Act, H.R. 4, 117th Cong. (2021) (passed the House, blocked by Senate filibuster despite majority Senate support -- the paradigm case for why categorical carve-outs are necessary); Freedom to Vote Act, S. 2747, 117th Cong. (2021) (same -- majority Senate support, blocked by filibuster); precedents from 2013 and 2017 (the Senate established categorical exceptions for nominations using exactly the majority procedure available for legislative categories). Empirical evidence: Every major voting rights and civil rights bill of the post-Reconstruction era has faced filibuster obstruction -- the Civil Rights Act of 1964 faced a 60-day filibuster; the Voting Rights Act of 1965 was threatened with filibuster; the Freedom to Vote Act and John R. Lewis Voting Rights Advancement Act both had majority Senate support but were blocked by the 60-vote cloture threshold; the filibuster was historically used disproportionately to block civil rights legislation for Black Americans. Enforcement mechanisms: Statutory codification of exceptions -- prevents a future Senate majority from restoring filibuster protection for these categories by a simple rule change without amending the underlying statute; Vice President authority to rule out of order -- creates an executive-branch enforcement pathway; simple majority sustains VP ruling -- means a bare majority can implement the carve-out without a supermajority. PolicyOS compliance: KERN-0004 (the filibuster has been the primary procedural tool for blocking constitutional rights legislation -- a categorical exception for rights implementation is a structural accountability requirement); DEMO-0001 (voting rights legislation specifically must be democratically enactable by a majority Senate without supermajority obstruction to ensure elections remain competitive and accountable). Adversarial review: Gap -- the category "legislation implementing rights guaranteed by the Constitution" is potentially broad enough to cover very different kinds of legislation; a future Senate majority could interpret it expansively to include essentially any legislation with a constitutional hook, effectively eliminating the filibuster entirely through creative categorization; the statute must define the categories with sufficient specificity to limit scope while covering the core cases. Loophole -- legislation could be drafted with both a voting rights component and unrelated riders so that the entire bill benefits from the filibuster carve-out; the carve-out must apply only to the eligible provisions, not to unrelated matter attached as riders, or be accompanied by a germaneness requirement for all provisions in a bill proceeding under the exception. Unintended consequence -- creating statutory categories exempt from filibuster creates a strong incentive for any majority to characterize its preferred legislation as "voting rights" or "rights implementation" to benefit from the exception; the carve-out must be enforced by neutral standards (committee determinations, GAO certification) rather than left to the majority's self-interested classification. Abuse path -- a bare Senate majority could use the VP ruling mechanism during a Senate session when a minority of senators are temporarily absent to establish precedent for expanded categories; the rule must require minimum floor presence for VP category rulings to be valid, preventing ambush precedent-setting.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="policy-family" id="fam-ethx">
<div class="family-header">
<span class="family-code">LEG</span>
<span class="family-title">ETHX: Congressional Ethics and Conflicts of Interest</span>
<span class="family-count">0/4 active</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-grid">
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-ETHX-0001">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-ETHX-0001</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Members of Congress and Senior Staff May Not Trade Individual Stocks While in Office</p><p class="rule-plain">Members of Congress and senior staff cannot trade individual stocks while in office. They can only hold diversified funds that they don't control.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Any Member of Congress, congressional leadership staff, or senior committee staff with access to non-public legislative information is prohibited from purchasing, selling, or holding individual corporate stocks, stock options, cryptocurrency, or commodity futures while holding office; permitted investments are limited to diversified mutual funds, index funds, U.S. Treasury securities, and real property not subject to federal regulation. Existing holdings must be divested within 180 days of taking office or placed in a qualified blind trust with an independent trustee. Violations are subject to: disgorgement of all profits; a civil penalty equal to three times the profit or avoided loss; referral to the DOJ for insider trading prosecution; and mandatory public disclosure. The STOCK Act must be strengthened to include these prohibitions and remove the "research exception." Any person harmed by insider trading on material non-public legislative information must have a private right of action in federal court for disgorgement and damages.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Legal basis: Stop Trading on Congressional Knowledge Act (STOCK Act), Pub. L. No. 112-105 (2012) (prohibiting members of Congress and staff from trading on material non-public information -- but retaining the "research exception" that creates a significant loophole and imposing only weak penalties; this rule strengthens and replaces its enforcement framework); 15 U.S.C. § 78j(b) (Securities Exchange Act Section 10(b), the general securities fraud provision under which congressional insider trading is theoretically prosecutable); 18 U.S.C. § 1348 (securities fraud statute). Empirical evidence: Studies have found that members of Congress outperform the market by statistically significant margins, with multiple analyses finding average excess returns of 6-12% annually before the STOCK Act's passage; Ziobrowski, A. J., et al. (2004). Abnormal returns from the common stock investments of the U.S. Senate. Journal of Financial and Quantitative Analysis, 39(4), 661-676 (foundational study documenting Senate outperformance); after the STOCK Act's passage in 2012, reporting was rapidly weakened and enforcement remained minimal -- a 2021 Business Insider investigation found more than 50 members had violated even the weak existing disclosure requirements without consequence; the STOCK Act's "research exception" allows members and staff to trade on policy research they conduct themselves, even when that research is based on non-public information. Enforcement mechanisms: Divestiture or blind trust requirement within 180 days -- removes the ongoing incentive structure; disgorgement of all profits -- removes any financial benefit from violations; civil penalty at 3x profit/avoided loss -- creates deterrence beyond disgorgement; DOJ referral for insider trading prosecution -- brings federal criminal enforcement into play; private right of action -- creates a plaintiff class with standing to enforce the requirement without relying on Congress to discipline itself. PolicyOS compliance: KERN-0001 (preventing financial corruption of legislative decision-making is a floor requirement for any system of governance that is accountable to constituents rather than to financial interests); KERN-0004 (democratic accountability requires that legislators not have personal financial stakes in the outcomes of legislation they enact). Adversarial review: Gap -- the rule applies to "senior committee staff with access to non-public legislative information" but does not cover all staff who may have incidental access to market-moving non-public information through their work; the rule must define "access to non-public legislative information" broadly enough to cover staff at any level who receive, process, or transmit material non-public legislative information. Loophole -- members could avoid the prohibition by trading through family members, business partners, or other proxies not covered by the direct prohibition; the rule must explicitly extend to cover trades executed by or for the benefit of any family member or entity in which the member has a financial interest, not only to the member's direct accounts. Unintended consequence -- requiring divestiture or blind trust placement may discourage qualified candidates who have built careers in finance or business from running for office; a reasonable accommodation of allowing existing holdings to be placed in managed blind trusts on Day 1 (rather than requiring immediate divestiture) addresses this concern without creating ongoing trading conflicts. Abuse path -- a future Congress could amend the STOCK Act to restore a broader research exception or reduce penalties after the initial enforcement period, effectively gutting the reform; the rule must specify that it cannot be suspended or waived by the Ethics Committee and that any amendment reducing penalty severity requires a recorded supermajority vote.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-ETHX-0002">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-ETHX-0002</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">The Office of Congressional Ethics Must Be Independent, Fully Funded, and Have Subpoena Power</p><p class="rule-plain">The Office of Congressional Ethics must be truly independent with guaranteed funding, subpoena power, and the authority to investigate and publicly report misconduct.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">The Office of Congressional Ethics (OCE) must be codified in statute as an independent entity, not a House resolution subject to repeal by majority vote, with: a permanent budget not subject to annual appropriations riders; subpoena authority to compel document production and witness testimony in ethics investigations; authority to refer criminal matters to the DOJ; and publication of all investigation findings regardless of House Ethics Committee follow-up. The OCE board must be composed of non-partisan former judges and attorneys; no current or former Members of Congress may serve. House and Senate rules prohibiting Members from retaliating against OCE witnesses must be enforceable by private right of action in federal district court.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Legal basis: House Resolution 895, 110th Congress (2008) (establishing the OCE as a House body by resolution, not statute -- making it fully subject to repeal or modification by any future House majority without procedural protection); House Rules Package, 115th Congress, January 2017 (the House Republican caucus voted to make the OCE subordinate to the House Ethics Committee and strip its independence -- the proposal was reversed within 24 hours after public backlash, but demonstrated the institutional fragility of a resolution-based body); 2 U.S.C. § 4711 (Congressional Accountability Act, establishing employment protections for congressional staff -- currently requiring mandatory mediation before federal court access, which this rule amends). Empirical evidence: In January 2017, the House Republican caucus voted by a 119-74 margin to gut the OCE; the proposal was withdrawn after public backlash and a tweet from President-elect Trump criticizing the timing, demonstrating the OCE's complete institutional vulnerability to majoritarian repeal; the OCE currently operates without subpoena authority, which means it can investigate only what witnesses voluntarily provide -- a critical enforcement gap; the OCE has no permanent budget and is funded through annual appropriations riders, creating leverage for appropriators to defund it; the OCE has no authority to independently pursue criminal referrals to the DOJ. Enforcement mechanisms: Statutory codification -- prevents repeal by House majority without Senate concurrence and presidential signature; permanent budget -- removes appropriations leverage; subpoena authority -- enables compelled document production and witness testimony; DOJ referral authority -- provides criminal enforcement pathway; private right of action for retaliation victims -- creates enforceable witness protection independent of the Ethics Committee. PolicyOS compliance: KERN-0001 (an ethics enforcement body that can be eliminated by a simple majority vote of the body it oversees provides no meaningful accountability -- independent statutory footing is a floor requirement for functional ethics enforcement); KERN-0004 (independent ethics enforcement of congressional conduct is a necessary accountability mechanism for democratic governance). Adversarial review: Gap -- codifying the OCE in statute still leaves it subject to amendment by a Congress that wants to defund or weaken it; the statute should include a supermajority requirement (e.g., 2/3 of each chamber) to amend or repeal OCE authority, or alternatively require an independent commission to trigger any amendment process. Loophole -- the House Ethics Committee, which receives OCE referrals, could simply table all OCE referrals without action, effectively making the OCE's investigations advisory only; the statute must require the Ethics Committee to publicly respond to all OCE referrals within a specified time period and publish its reasons for any decision not to proceed. Unintended consequence -- a fully independent OCE with subpoena authority could be weaponized for political harassment, with partisan appointees pursuing investigations of opposition members for political advantage rather than genuine ethics violations; the statute must include independent appointment procedures for OCE board members, term limits, bipartisan balance requirements, and appellate review procedures for members subject to investigation. Abuse path -- the OCE's independence could be circumvented if the Department of Justice declines to act on all criminal referrals from a politically sympathetic Congress; the statute should specify that OCE criminal referrals are publicly disclosed, enabling civil society and press scrutiny of DOJ inaction, and that DOJ non-action does not preclude state attorney general prosecution of state-law violations.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-ETHX-0003">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-ETHX-0003</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Members of Congress Must Recuse From Votes in Which They Have a Direct Financial Interest</p><p class="rule-plain">Members of Congress must not vote on bills where they have a direct financial interest that could personally benefit them or their immediate family.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Any Member of Congress must recuse from voting on any legislation in which they, their spouse, or their immediate family members have a direct personal financial interest exceeding $5,000; recusal decisions must be filed publicly with the Clerk of the House or Secretary of the Senate within 48 hours of the relevant vote. The House and Senate Ethics Committees must publish quarterly conflict-of-interest registries listing all members with identified financial interests in pending major legislation. Failure to recuse when required is an ethics violation subject to public censure; deliberate concealment of a conflict is grounds for expulsion proceedings and referral to the DOJ for criminal prosecution. Any affected constituent may bring a private right of action in federal court for declaratory relief against a vote cast in violation of this requirement. This requirement supplements, not replaces, financial disclosure requirements.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Legal basis: 18 U.S.C. § 208 (prohibiting executive branch employees from participating in matters in which they have a financial interest -- this rule extends the same principle to the legislative branch, which is currently exempt from this statute); 5 U.S.C. app. 4 (Ethics in Government Act, requiring financial disclosure -- this rule adds a recusal duty triggered by disclosed conflicts); Ethics in Government Act of 1978, Pub. L. No. 95-521 (establishing financial disclosure requirements that create the factual basis for applying the recusal requirement); House Ethics Manual (existing ethics guidelines on conflicts of interest -- largely advisory and not enforceable by private parties). Empirical evidence: The legislative branch is currently exempt from the executive branch financial conflict-of-interest statute (18 U.S.C. § 208) -- members may vote on legislation directly benefiting their personal investments with no legal prohibition; the STOCK Act requires disclosure of trades but does not prohibit or require recusal for votes on legislation affecting held securities; multiple documented cases exist where members voted on legislation -- including pandemic relief, tax legislation, and defense contracts -- while holding investments directly benefiting from the outcome; the absence of a recusal requirement has created significant public credibility damage to the legislative process. Enforcement mechanisms: Mandatory public filing within 48 hours -- creates a documentary record for enforcement; quarterly conflict-of-interest registries -- enables advance identification of conflicts before votes; private right of action for affected constituents -- creates a plaintiff class with standing to challenge conflicted votes without relying on Congress to discipline itself; expulsion and DOJ referral for deliberate concealment -- creates a meaningful deterrence against concealment. PolicyOS compliance: KERN-0001 (a legislative body whose members vote on legislation in which they have undisclosed personal financial stakes cannot function as a legitimate representative institution -- recusal requirements are a floor for any system of democratic governance); KERN-0004 (votes cast under undisclosed financial conflicts are not democratically accountable -- constituents are not being represented, they are being subject to self-interested action by their nominal representative). Adversarial review: Gap -- the $5,000 threshold may be too high in low-dollar-impact legislation (e.g., environmental regulations affecting small business property values) or too low in high-dollar legislation (e.g., sweeping tax reform where the member has millions in affected investments) -- a single fixed threshold is a blunt instrument; the threshold should be defined as a percentage of the member's total declared net worth rather than a fixed dollar amount, or alternatively set at a lower floor with a separate disclosure-only tier for interests between $1,000 and $5,000. Loophole -- members could transfer assets to family members or entities just before a relevant vote and transfer them back afterward, temporarily removing the interest from the recusal threshold; the rule must apply to any direct beneficial interest, including interests held through family members or entities controlled by the member, and must specify a lookback period (e.g., 12 months) for pre-vote transfers. Unintended consequence -- aggressive recusal requirements could deprive a chamber of the votes of members with unavoidable conflicts on major cross-cutting legislation (e.g., a member who owns a home in a district affected by infrastructure legislation has a financial interest in essentially all federal spending bills); the rule must specify a de minimis exception for conflicts that are shared broadly by constituents and are not the primary subject of the legislation. Abuse path -- the private right of action for constituents could be weaponized for political harassment, with opponents filing recusal challenges against every vote of a targeted member in hopes of invalidating legislation or generating negative press; the right of action must be limited to declaratory relief and require a showing of concrete harm, and frivolous challenges must be subject to fee-shifting against the challenging party.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-ETHX-0004">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-ETHX-0004</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">All Congressional Staff Must Be Paid No Less Than $65,000 Annually</p><p class="rule-plain">Every person who works for Congress must be paid at least $65,000 per year to ensure decent pay and reduce vulnerability to corruption.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">The minimum annual salary for any full-time congressional staff member, including staff in district offices, committee staff, personal office staff, and leadership office staff, must be no less than $65,000, indexed annually to the Washington D.C. cost of living index; unpaid internships in congressional offices are prohibited. Congressional staff must be covered by the same workplace anti-discrimination, anti-harassment, and whistleblower protection laws that apply to private sector employees; the Congressional Accountability Act must be amended to provide congressional employees with full federal court access for employment claims without mandatory mediation. Staff pay information must be published semi-annually on the public congressional salary database. Violation of the minimum pay requirement subjects the employing office to automatic civil penalty and referral to the OCE; congressional staff subject to pay violations must have a private right of action for back pay, penalties, and attorneys' fees in federal court.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Legal basis: Congressional Accountability Act of 1995, Pub. L. No. 104-1 (applying many federal workplace laws to congressional employees but with significant limitations, including mandatory mediation before federal court access, which this rule amends); 2 U.S.C. § 4531 et seq. (setting framework for congressional employee compensation and human resources -- provides the statutory vehicle for the minimum salary requirement); Congressional Budget Justification (Senate), various years (documenting actual staff salary levels -- publicly available and showing the wide range of compensation across offices). Empirical evidence: Until the Legislative Branch Appropriations Act of 2022 set a $45,000 minimum for House employees, many congressional staff in Washington D.C. -- one of the most expensive cities in the country -- earned $20,000-$30,000 annually; low pay at congressional offices has historically meant that only people with independent wealth or family support (disproportionately white, upper-income individuals) can afford to work as congressional staff, creating a systematically unrepresentative policy-development workforce; research by the Congressional Management Foundation has documented that underpaid congressional staff are more likely to leave for lobbying and private sector positions that leverage their congressional access, creating a revolving door between Congress and the industries it regulates; unpaid internships concentrated in high-cost Washington D.C. further limit the pipeline of congressional policy talent to the economically privileged. Enforcement mechanisms: Automatic civil penalty for violating offices -- creates an enforcement mechanism that does not depend on DOJ prioritization; private right of action for pay violations -- creates individual plaintiffs with standing to enforce the minimum pay requirement; OCE referral -- creates a public accountability record for pay violations; semi-annual public salary database -- enables monitoring by civil society and press. PolicyOS compliance: KERN-0001 (adequate pay for congressional staff is a structural prerequisite for a functional legislative branch -- a Congress staffed by policy expertise is a floor requirement for governance); KERN-0004 (a congressional staff composed primarily of individuals wealthy enough to work for poverty wages is not representative of the constituents Congress serves, undermining the democratic accountability function). Adversarial review: Gap -- the $65,000 minimum is a floor indexed to D.C. cost of living for Washington staff, but district office staff are located across the country in cities with very different costs of living; a flat $65,000 minimum indexed only to D.C. may significantly over- or underpay district staff in different markets; the index should apply separately to each office's location, using the relevant metropolitan area cost-of-living index rather than a single D.C. index. Loophole -- a member could comply with the $65,000 minimum by classifying some positions as "part-time" and paying $65,000 on a full-time-equivalent basis while actually requiring more hours; the rule must define minimum salary on a per-hour basis (minimum hourly equivalent) rather than as an annual amount, with overtime pay required for hours above 40 per week. Unintended consequence -- mandating higher minimum salaries without increasing the aggregate MRA (Member's Representational Allowance) budget could force some offices to reduce total staff count, potentially leaving fewer people to serve constituents; the Clerk of the House and Senate must be required to report to Congress on MRA adequacy within 180 days of the rule's effective date, with a recommended adjustment to ensure offices can maintain comparable staff levels. Abuse path -- a member could retaliate against staff who report pay violations to the OCE by classifying their positions differently, reassigning them to unfavorable locations, or constructively discharging them; the rule must include robust anti-retaliation protections specifying that any adverse employment action within 24 months of an OCE complaint triggers a rebuttable presumption of retaliation, with the burden on the employing office to demonstrate a legitimate non-retaliatory reason.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="policy-family" id="fam-lbby">
<div class="family-header">
<span class="family-code">LEG</span>
<span class="family-title">LBBY: Lobbying Reform</span>
<span class="family-count">0/2 active</span>
</div>
<div class="rule-grid">
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-LBBY-0001">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-LBBY-0001</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">Senior Executive Branch Officials and Congressional Leaders Face a Lifetime Lobbying Ban on Their Agency or Committee</p><p class="rule-plain">Senior executive branch officials and congressional leaders face a lifetime ban on lobbying on behalf of foreign governments after leaving office.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Any former Member of Congress who served in a leadership role (Speaker, Majority/Minority Leader, Committee Chair or Ranking Member), any former Cabinet Secretary or Deputy Secretary, and any former senior White House official (Assistant to the President or above) must be permanently banned from lobbying the specific agency, committee, or legislative body they led; the current two-year and one-year "cooling off" periods are replaced with a permanent sector-specific ban. Former officials may never lobby on behalf of foreign governments or foreign state-owned enterprises in any capacity. The DOJ must enforce these provisions; violations are a federal criminal offense carrying up to five years imprisonment. Any person or organization subject to lobbying in violation of this ban must have a private right of action to void agreements and recover fees paid.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Legal basis: 18 U.S.C. § 207 (the current post-employment lobbying restrictions -- one year for most executive branch officials, two years for senior officials; this rule extends the sector-specific ban for covered leadership positions to permanent); 22 U.S.C. § 611 et seq. (Foreign Agents Registration Act -- requiring registration for foreign lobbying; this rule adds a categorical criminal prohibition for former officials); Lobbying Disclosure Act of 1995, Pub. L. No. 104-65 (establishing the current lobbying disclosure and restriction framework -- the basis for the rules this position strengthens). Empirical evidence: Former Members of Congress currently face only a one-year (Senate) or two-year (House) cooling-off period before directly lobbying their former colleagues; a 2021 OpenSecrets analysis found that more than 400 former Members of Congress had become registered lobbyists; the revolving door between Congress and lobbying is extensively documented -- former members command premium lobbying rates precisely because their personal relationships with sitting members provide access unavailable to ordinary lobbyists; former Cabinet secretaries and senior White House officials routinely move into lobbying roles representing the industries they formerly regulated, with documented examples across Democratic and Republican administrations. Enforcement mechanisms: Federal criminal offense with up to five years imprisonment -- creates meaningful deterrence for former officials and their clients; private right of action to void agreements and recover fees -- creates a financial deterrent by putting the lobbying contract itself at risk; DOJ enforcement -- provides prosecutorial backup for criminal violations. PolicyOS compliance: KERN-0001 (the revolving door between government leadership and lobbying undermines the basic accountability function of public service -- former officials who use government relationships to represent private interests are converting public-interest service into private-interest leverage); KERN-0004 (permanent sector-specific bans ensure that leadership officials make decisions in office based on the public interest rather than future lobbying career opportunities). Adversarial review: Gap -- the permanent sector-specific ban covers only the "specific agency, committee, or legislative body" the official led, which could be interpreted narrowly to allow a former Committee Chair to lobby on the same subject matter through a different committee with jurisdiction; the ban must be defined by subject matter and industry sector, not merely by institutional unit, to prevent jurisdiction-shopping by covered officials. Loophole -- former officials could conduct substantive lobbying while formally employing a registered lobbyist to make the contacts, with the former official providing strategy, intelligence, and access in a role that does not meet the technical definition of "lobbying contact"; the rule must extend to any compensated advisory or strategic role in which the former official uses their government relationships or non-public knowledge, regardless of whether they personally make lobbying contacts. Unintended consequence -- a permanent sector-specific ban may reduce the pool of qualified candidates willing to serve in leadership roles, if individuals expect a permanent career restriction; the ban must be accompanied by post-service compensation provisions (retirement benefits, public interest employment pathways) that make public service financially viable without requiring a subsequent lobbying career. Abuse path -- the DOJ could decline to prosecute violations by politically connected former officials, particularly those affiliated with the current administration; the private right of action for organizations subject to illegal lobbying must provide a meaningful independent enforcement pathway, and violations must be publicly disclosed regardless of prosecution decisions.</p>
</div>
<div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-LBBY-0002">
<div class="rule-header">
<code class="rule-id">LEGL-LBBY-0002</code>
</div>
<p class="rule-title">All Lobbying Contacts With Members of Congress Must Be Disclosed Within 48 Hours</p><p class="rule-plain">All meetings between lobbyists and members of Congress must be disclosed publicly within 24 hours, including who met, what was discussed, and what the lobbyist wanted.</p>
<p class="rule-stmt">Any registered lobbyist who makes a lobbying contact with a Member of Congress, congressional staff, or senior executive branch official must file a disclosure with the Clerk of the House or Secretary of the Senate within 48 hours identifying: the lobbyist, the client, the official contacted, the legislation or regulatory matter discussed, and the approximate duration of the contact. Disclosures must be searchable in real time on a public database. Bundled campaign contributions from lobbyists and their clients must be disclosed within 24 hours of delivery; contributions made within 30 days of a lobbying contact are presumptively disclosed as related unless the lobbyist certifies otherwise. Failure to disclose is subject to $25,000 per-contact civil penalties and referral to the DOJ for willful violations. Any member of the public must have a private right of action to compel disclosure and seek civil penalties for unreported contacts.</p>
<p class="rule-notes">Legal basis: Lobbying Disclosure Act of 1995, Pub. L. No. 104-65, as amended by the Honest Leadership and Open Government Act of 2007, Pub. L. No. 110-81 (the current framework requiring quarterly disclosure of lobbying activities -- this rule replaces quarterly with 48-hour per-contact disclosure); 2 U.S.C. § 1601 et seq. (LDA disclosure provisions); Bipartisan Campaign Reform Act of 2002, 52 U.S.C. § 30101 et seq. (campaign finance disclosure framework -- this rule extends disclosure requirements to bundled contributions from lobbyists within 30 days of a lobbying contact). Empirical evidence: The current Lobbying Disclosure Act requires quarterly reports covering aggregate lobbying activity but does not require per-contact disclosure or real-time searchability; the quarterly reporting window means that lobbying contacts made months before a floor vote may not be publicly disclosed until long after the vote has occurred; bundled campaign contributions from lobbyists are a documented mechanism for converting lobbying access into direct campaign finance influence -- the "bundling" practice allows lobbyists to aggregate contributions from clients and deliver them to candidates as a packaged benefit; the 2007 Honest Leadership and Open Government Act improved disclosure but did not require real-time per-contact reporting. Enforcement mechanisms: $25,000 per-contact civil penalty -- creates per-violation deterrence proportional to the cost of professional lobbying; DOJ referral for willful violations -- provides criminal enforcement backstop; private right of action for any member of the public -- creates a distributed enforcement model without relying on government initiative; real-time searchable database -- enables civil society monitoring and rapid press investigation of lobbying patterns. PolicyOS compliance: KERN-0001 (public transparency in the lobbying process is a floor requirement for any system of democratic accountability -- constituents cannot hold representatives accountable for lobbying access they cannot observe); KERN-0004 (the 48-hour per-contact disclosure requirement ensures that lobbying activity is publicly visible in time for constituents to engage with their representatives before votes are cast, not months afterward). Adversarial review: Gap -- the 48-hour disclosure requirement applies to "registered lobbyists" but many influencers with substantial policy access are not registered under the LDA's technical definition (requiring at least 20% of time on lobbying activities for a single client) -- strategic consultants, former officials, and "policy advisors" can have the same functional influence as registered lobbyists without triggering disclosure; the rule must extend disclosure requirements to any compensated contact by a person with government relations responsibilities, regardless of formal registration status. Loophole -- lobbyists could conduct substantive advocacy through informal channels (private dinners, phone calls classified as "courtesy calls," charity events) that may not meet the technical definition of "lobbying contact" under the LDA, allowing the substance of lobbying to continue without triggering disclosure; the rule must define "lobbying contact" broadly to include any communication in which policy matters are discussed, regardless of formality or setting. Unintended consequence -- 48-hour per-contact disclosure could significantly increase the administrative burden on lobbyists and congressional offices and could chill legitimate constituent communications if overly broadly defined; the disclosure requirement must include a de minimis exception for communications that are solely informational (constituent service inquiries, scheduling requests) without substantive policy advocacy content. Abuse path -- a party in control of the House Clerk's or Senate Secretary's office could delay processing or searchability of disclosures from opposition lobbyists while expediting favorable disclosures; the database must be maintained by an independent agency (GAO or an independent disclosure body) with mandated processing times and automated real-time posting without manual review gates.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="policy-family" id="fam-dmj"><h3>Dismantling Judicial Override</h3><div class="rule-grid"></div></div><div class="policy-family" id="fam-drf"><h3>Drafting Reform</h3><div class="rule-grid"></div></div><div class="policy-family" id="fam-pro"><h3>Procedural Reform</h3><div class="rule-grid"></div></div><div class="policy-family" id="fam-rpl"><h3>Replacement Procedures</h3><div class="rule-grid"><div class="policy-card" id="LEGL-RPLS-0003"><div class="rule-header"><code class="rule-id">LEGL-RPLS-0003</code></div><p class="rule-title">Repeal the Alien Enemies Act framework and related emergency-authority structures that enable abuse against non-citiz...</p><p class="rule-plain">The Alien Enemies Act, which allows the president to detain or deport people based on nationality during wartime, must be repealed along with similar laws that enable emergency power abuse.</p><p class="rule-stmt">Repeal the Alien Enemies Act framework and related emergency-authority structures that enable abuse against non-citizens through vague wartime or insurrection logic</p><p class="rule-notes">Source: DB entry LEG-RPL-001, status: PROPOSED. Pending editorial review.</p></div></div></div><div class="policy-family" id="fam-sen"><h3>Senate Reform</h3><div class="rule-grid"></div></div></div>
